<HEADLINE> Dutchman Van Bon Wins Sixth Stage of Tour de France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Italian Alberto Elli gained overall
leadership in the Tour de France cycle race from Frenchman Laurent
Jalabert on Thursday after Dutchman Leon van Bon won the 198.5-
kilometer sixth stage from Vitre to Tours.
</P>
<P>
Markus Zberg of Switzerland finished second of the stage and
Emmanuel Magnien of France came in third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Davenport Advances into Wimbledon Women's Singles Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Lindsay Davenport
of the United States booked a women's singles final meeting with
Venus Williams on Saturday after a straight 6-4, 6-2 victory over
Australian Jelena Dokic.
</P>
<P>
The opening set was a scrappy affair that saw seven breaks of
serve in total.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Australian made the first breakthrough and
raced into a 2-0 lead but Davenport began to find her range and
responded to lead 3-2 until the game moved into a topsy-turvy
affair with neither player able to hold their serve.
</P>
<P>
Reigning champion Davenport finally obliged to take the opening
set 6-4 in 28 minutes.
</P>
<P>
And Davenport seized the advantage once again at the start of
the second set as a backhand into the net from the Australian gave
the American a break in the third game.
</P>
<P>
Dokic was causing Davenport most problems when she was able to
move her around the court but she was still often reliant on
Davenport errors.
</P>
<P>
As the game went on these were becoming fewer and a wayward
cross-court volley from Dokic gave Davenport another break and
move into a 5-2 lead in the second.
</P>
<P>
Without displaying the sort of form that she will need to
defeat Venus Williams, Davenport clinched victory at the first
attempt with a clinical last serve. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
