<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armenia to Open Embassy in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 7 (Xinhua)-- Arshak, the acting Armenian Charge
D'affaires to the United Arab Emirates announced on
Friday his country has decided to open its embassy in the UAE,
its first one in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to Emirates WAM News Agency, the Armenian
official said his country has selected the UAE as the venue of
its first embassy in the Gulf, expressing its high esteem
of the UAE's balanced policy.
</P>
<P>
"The UAE has gained an international respect due to its balanced
policy," the envoy said.
</P>
<P>
"The UAE enjoys stability and continuous development.
The opening of our embassy in the UAE would help in enhancing
relations between the two countries in various fields," he added.
</P>
<P>
The envoy disclosed the official opening of his
country's embassy in the UAE will be next December during a visit
of the Armenian foreign minister to the UAE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Talks Proceed Smoothly in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The third round of the U.N.-
sponsored proximity talks for the reunification of the Cyprus
island have been proceeding smoothly in Geneva for the first three
days, local media reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The exploratory phase of the talks, which started on July 5 in
Geneva, is coming to an end and the talks are expected to go into
the substance of the Cyprus issue, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The eastern Mediterranean island of Cyprus has been split into
the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities since 1974 when Turkey
invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake
of a short-lived coup by supporters of union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-brokered proximity talks between Cyprus
President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
were held in New York last December and Geneva last February.
</P>
<P>
Fears of a likely collapse of the third round of talks from the
very beginning followed the earlier statements by Denktash that he
might not head to Geneva for the talks.
</P>
<P>
Denktash had also said that he would only go to Geneva to
express his dissatisfactions with the removal of the addendum from
the latest U.N. Security Council resolution on Cyprus, which
expressed his view that the U.N. peace force in Cyprus could not
operate without the consent of his breakaway state.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Geneva, however, both Clerides and
Denktash have so far appeared satisfied with the first phase of the
third round of talks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's Special Adviser
for Cyprus Alvaro de Soto Friday announced in Geneva that the talks
will be adjourned next Wednesday and will resume on July 24.
</P>
<P>
The suspension of the talks was proposed by the Greek Cypriot
side due to some political developments expected to be made known
when the time is right, political sources said.
</P>
<P>
Denktash asked for suspending the talks so as to attend his
breakaway state's "celebration" for the Turkish invasion of the
island's northern third in July 1974.
</P>
<P>
De Soto said "there are political consideration which led to the
break and it is a subject of compromise."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Spares No Efforts to Support Palestinian Course: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel Ilah
Khatib stressed here on Friday his kingdom will do its utmost to
support the Palestinians to restore their legitimate rights,
including the establishment of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in a meeting with visiting Secretary of the
Executive Committee of the Palestinian Liberation Organization
Mahmoud Abbas.
</P>
<P>
Abbas arrived here earlier in the day to brief Jordan on the
principled Palestinian stand during the upcoming summit between the
United States, Israel and the Palestinians slated for July 11 at
the David Camp near Washington, Jordan's official news agency Petra
reported without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
The visit by the Palestinian official to Amman is part of a
bilateral consultation mechanism between Jordan and the
Palestinians over the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom has been a major peace broker between Israel and its
Arab neighbors since it signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994
as the second Arab state after Egypt to reach peace with the Jewish
state.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein held
telephone conversations with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, calling on parties
concerned to exert their utmost efforts to pave the way for a
success of the David Camp summit.
</P>
<P>
The monarch stressed that Jordan hopes the three-way summit
will result in a just and durable peace agreement between Israel
and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Jordan believes a solution to the Palestinian issue is the core
to a just, durable and comprehensive peace for all peoples in the
region, including Israelis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar Welcomes Upcoming U.S.-Palestinian-Israeli Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Qatar welcomes the forthcoming
three-way summit by U.S., Israeli and Palestinian leaders next
Tuesday in Camp David near Washington, said a senior Qatari
official Friday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Hamad Bin Jassim al-Thani expressed hope that
all parties concerned will go into the talks seriously and
earnestly.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which will begin next Tuesday with the participation
of U.S. President Bill Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, will try to resolve the
thorny issues in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks such as
Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees, borders, Jewish settlements and
water.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will try to reach a framework agreement before the
September target date for a final peace accord.
</P>
<P>
And he voiced hope that all outstanding issues will be mulled
over at the summit with a view to producing positive results that
might push forward the peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
He highlighted the major role played by Clinton in mediating
between the two sides and acclaimed his eagerness for clinching an
all-out peace deal between the Palestinians and Israel, the Qatari
News Agency monitored here reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Administration will seek through convening the summit
to bring closer the positions of the two sides ahead of Clinton's
elapse of term in office next January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
