<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Palestinian Housing Minister Abdul Rahman Hamad said a
power station will be operated by the Palestinians for the first
time in decades early next summer to stop reliance on Israeli
supplies.
</P>
<P>
Hamad told reporters Friday that the new facility would bring to
an end Israeli monopoly of power supplies to the Palestinian self-
rule areas, adding that by 2003 the electricity utility would be
fully dependant on national resources.
</P>
<P>
The minister, also head of the Palestinian Energy Authority
(PEA), mentioned the ongoing efforts to set up power grids and
ensure funds for power projects, especially in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Hamad said his ministry has obtained some grants and loans to
provide all Palestinian rural areas with power and the year 2003
has been set as the deadline for making electricity available to
all villages.
</P>
<P>
The PEA has signed contracts with some local and foreign
companies on the construction of a 144-megawatt power station at
Gaza Valley next year at a cost of 92 million U.S. dollars, said
the minister.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Cairo will host a conference entitled "Egyptian
insurance industry, seeking a place on the world market" on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The conference, sponsored by the U.S. Commerce Department and
the Egyptian Insurance Union and Insurance Control Authority, will
discuss the development of insurance in Egypt and future prospects
for the industry as well as the legislation governing it.
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Palestinian Housing Minister Abdul Rahman Hamad and Head
of the Palestinian Energy Authority (PEA) told reporters here on
Friday that the drilling process at the recently-discovered natural
gas field off Gaza coast would kick off next month.
</P>
<P>
"British Gas will launch the drilling operation to fathom the
reserve of the field which lies under full Palestinian control next
or minimally the following month," he added.
</P>
<P>
The test scheme would run until late this summer, he said,
stressing that all studies and research so far have turned out
positive.
</P>
<P>
Initial examinations showed that the natural gas reserves off
the Gaza Strip coast could well cover local needs, which would
allow exports to foreign markets, he said without elaborating on
the figures.
</P>
<P>
Commercial production of Palestinian natural gas would start in
late 2002 or early 2003, he added.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- Dubai emirate of the United Arab Emirates (UAE) signed
a memo of understanding with Jordan on cooperation in trade,
education, management, information technology and custom fields.
</P>
<P>
The memo was the second of its kind in three years after the one
signed between the emirate and Egypt last May.
</P>
<P>
The document involved a potential cooperation agreement between
Jordan's Export Promotion Agency and trade centers and the Dubai-
based Jabal Ali Free Trade Zone (FTZ) to encourage Jordanian
exports via the Jabal Ali FTZ.
</P>
<P>
Under the memo, the two sides would draw up plans to establish a
branch of the Jordanian Science and Technology University in Dubai
Internet City, as well as to work out joint educational programs on
computer and Internet sciences. 
</P>
