<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Provide 1 Bln Euro For Debt Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Union will support to
the enhanced Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) Initiative
with total contribution worth of more than one billion euros (one
euro equals some 0.95 U.S. dollars), the European Commission said
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
EU Commissioner for Development Cooperation and Humanitarian
Aid Poul Nielson signed Friday with World Bank administered Trust
Fund for this support to HIPC Initiative.
</P>
<P>
Through the Trust Fund, 680 million euros will help
multilateral development banks give debt relief to the Asia,
Pacific and Caribbean countries, while 54 million euros will go to
Latin American and East Asian countries. Another 348 million euros
will be used to reduce debt owed to the EU.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission said the EU is the single largest
contributor to the HIPC Trust Fund providing almost one third of
the total amount pledged by all donors. The EU also leads in terms
of actual payments. Following the EU's signature today, the first
payment to the Trust Fund of more than 300 million euros will be
made, which is by far the single highest amount paid into the
Trust Fund.
</P>
<P>
Nielson said he hopes the EU's example will encourage the Group
of Seven industrialized nations (G7 Group) and other donors to
take decisive steps to pay what they have pledged. "I now urge
others to pay into this Trust Fund. This is a start -- but
financing will only be secured if other donors now rapidly
contribute to the Fund. We must move to actual payments and build
on this momentum," he said.
</P>
<P>
The HIPC Initiative was launched in September 1996. It
represented a concerted effort by all donors and multilateral
creditors to address the problem of external indebtedness of low-
income countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
