<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Study Tallies High Expense of Computer Viruses, Hacking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Viruses and computer hackers
will cost businesses around the world more than 1.5 trillion U.S.
dollars this year, according to a study released Friday.
</P>
<P>
A global survey of 4,900 information technology professionals
across 30 countries, conducted by U.S. trade magazine
InformationWeek and fielded by accounting firm
PricewaterhouseCoopers, found that the key costs involved in
correcting IT systems infected a virus are found in lost
productivity as a result of downtime for computer systems, as well
as lost sales opportunities.
</P>
<P>
In North America, technology professionals this year will
suffer system downtime of 3.24 percent, while downtime to 3.28
percent on a worldwide basis. To look at the impact another way,
the study found that this year alone 6,882 person years of
productivity will be lost in North America and nearly 40,000 will
be lost worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The study estimates that some 50,000 firms in the United States
are sufficiently large enough to be impacted by and accurately
tally up the cost of a software virus. In total, the bill to these
U.S. firms this year for viruses and computer hacking will amount
to 266 billion dollars, or more than 2.5 percent of the nation's
GDP. The price tag worldwide soars to 1.6 trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 266-billion-dollar figure represents the impact of viruses
on U.S. businesses with more than 1,000 employees, or about 50,000
firms. "These are companies with infrastructures of IT
professionals who, because of the dollar impact, are increasingly
tracking the problem and can provide an accurate assessment of the
scope of the issue," InformationWeek said in a report. "In reality,
the true impact of viruses on U.S. businesses, including medium-
sized companies and businesses, is much greater."
</P>
<P>
Viruses and the hackers that deploy them were nonce viewed as
clever pranksters, according to the study, but are now seen as
real threats. "Information technology now runs businesses around
the globe," said the report. "Whatever stops the computer systems
stops business." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
