<HEADLINE> Clinton Postpones Execution of Federal Inmate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has
decided to postpone the execution of a federal prisoner until the
Justice Department announce new federal clemency guidelines, the
White House said Friday.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Jake Siewert said Clinton will stay the
August 5 scheduled execution of Juan Raul Garza, who was convicted
in 1993 in Brownsville, Texas for killing three men.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department is expected to complete work on the
clemency guidelines within a week or so.
</P>
<P>
"Given that time line, we expect the president will stay Mr.
Garza's sentence to make sure that process has an opportunity to
play itself out," Siewert said.
</P>
<P>
"We want Mr. Garza to have an opportunity to submit a request
for clemency. We want to make sure that there are firm guidelines
in place."
</P>
<P>
Garza's execution will be the first one of a federal death row
inmate since 1963. He is one of 21 federal prisoners awaiting
execution.
</P>
<P>
Since the death penalty was reinstated by the Supreme Court in
1976, there have been 651 state executions, but not even one at
the federal level.
</P>
<P>
A heated debate is currently going on in the United States over
the fairness of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton, who is a death-penalty supporter, has called
for  "broadest possible use" of DNA evidence to ensure its
fairness and safeguards to ensure defendants are adequately
represented.  
</P>
</TEXT>
