<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. to Conduct Crucial Test of Missile Defense System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A four-hour launch window opens at 7:00 p.m. local time (0200
GMT Saturday) at Vandenberg Air Force Base in California State
where a target missile is poised for launch.
</P>
<P>
Weather permitting, a Minuteman intercontinental missile with a
dummy warhead on top was scheduled to be launched from the base
toward the Pacific Marshall Islands sometime during the test
window.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. "hit-to-kill" weapon would be fired atop its own missile
from Kwajalein Atoll 6880 kilometers away about 20 minutes after
the Vandenberg launch in an attempt to maneuver, intercept and
smash into the "enemy" warhead.
</P>
<P>
The 55-kilogram weapon, built by Raytheon Co., is designed to
hit and smash the target into space dust at a speed of 24,000 kph
in a flash that would be captured by long-range cameras.
</P>
<P>
The first such test last October was successful, although there
was a problem with finding the approaching warhead. A second such
test failed early this year.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace claimed that activists had infiltrated the base to
try to stop the 100-million-U.S.-dollar test, but Vandenberg Air
Force Base spokesman John Cherry said there was no evidence of
intruders in the heavily patrolled area around the launch pad.
</P>
<P>
The results of Friday's test will weigh heavily in U.S.
President Bill Clinton's planned decision in the coming months on
whether to begin building the NMD.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said earlier that he will take into account the
feasibility of such a system, its cost, its impact on the overall
national security system and an assessment of the threat to the
Untied States when he makes his decision.
</P>
<P>
The anti-missile system is designed to provide protection for
all 50 U.S. states against ballistic missile attacks. A base with
20 interceptor missiles would be built in Alaska State, along with
a new radar to help guide the missiles to their target. By 2007,
under the current schedule, the system would be expanded to 100
interceptor missiles. The Pentagon estimates the cost at 36
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Arms control experts said the U.S. NMD, opposed by the
international community, will not only spark a new arms race, but
also threaten security and stimulate nuclear proliferation,
instead of promoting security and stemming the spread of nuclear
weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
