<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Palaeoanthropological Site Discovered in East Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A palaeoanthropological site as
old as some four million years has been discovered at Galili
locality in the Mulu Basin, about 250 km east of Addis Ababa, the
Ethiopian Information and Culture Ministry announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
A research, which was conducted since 1998 by an Ethiopian
anthropologist Yohannes Haile-Selassie, unveiled the new site
which yielded a number of hominid and faunal remains, a press
release by the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Various survey projects and consequent discoveries attested
that the well-recognized sites in Ethiopia such as Hadar, the
middle Awash, Omo and Konso constitute only a few compared with
the over-all palaeoanthropological potential in the country.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary analysis of the hominid specimens from Galili shows
that these specimen are chronologically more primitive than
Lucy's species, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Lucy species, found in eastern Afar State in 1974, is believed
to be the oldest, most complete human ancestor yet discovered in
the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
