<HEADLINE> Iranian Parties Urge Thorough Probe into Student Dorm Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Two reformist parties in Iran on
Friday urged government agencies to make thorough investigations
into a student dormitory incident that sparked nation-wide riots
last July.
</P>
<P>
The roots of the incident must be found out and all persons
responsible should be identified and punished, said a statement
issued by the Islamic Labor Party on the occasion of the first
anniversary of the incident.
</P>
<P>
It added that merely trying some soldiers and police commanders
are far from being enough, because the people want those behind the
scenes to be exposed.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Iran Solidarity Party, in a separate statement, also
criticized the court proceeding of the incident, saying the public
has not yet been satisfied with the process, the Islamic Republic
News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The file of the dormitory case is still open while no
satisfactory results have been achieved, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Anti-riot police and plainclothes men stormed a Tehran
University dormitory on July 8 last year to crack down on student
protests against press restrictions, especially the closure of the
outspoken daily Salam by the conservative authorities.
</P>
<P>
The incident triggered six-day riots around the country, the
worst unrest Iran had experienced since the 1979 Islamic
revolution. At least one person died and a lot of others were
injured in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
Iran's military court ended its three-month trial of some 20
police commanders involved in the dormitory incident in May, but no
verdict has been issued yet.
</P>
<P>
Those tried included former Tehran police commander Brigadier
General Farhad Nazari and commander of the special unit of the
Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps Colonel Jamshid Khodabakhshi.
</P>
<P>
All of the suspects denied the allegation that they were
responsible for the dormitory incident, insisting that they had
acted on orders of superiors and in accordance with their legal
duties.
</P>
<P>
They blamed their charges on rumors and accusations and
expressed hope that they would be acquitted.
</P>
<P>
Iran's reformists insist that the investigations and trial are
far from being enough, demanding that those behind the scenes and
really responsible for the incident should be found out and
punished.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Iran's Ministry of Science, Research and Technology
also called for an in-depth investigation into the incident.
</P>
<P>
There must be a firm probe to track down the root cause of the
incident, the ministry said in a statement issued on the occasion
of the first anniversary of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Students of Tehran University have decided to observe July 8 as
the "National Day Against Violence" to mark the tragic incident,
IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
The students will offer flowers to the people on the main
squares of Tehran on July 8 to mark the anniversary.
</P>
<P>
"We will offer flowers to the people with a smile" to mark the
anniversary of the incident and "will avoid any action which may
lead to violence," a student organization called "the Office to
Foster Unity" told the agency on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
