representative of the secretary-general for children and armed
conflict, Olara Otunnu, Friday welcomed the ratification by Canada
of a new treaty designed to prevent anyone under 18 from
participating in hostilities.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd Axworthy, Canada's minister for foreign affairs and
international trade, deposited Canada's instrument of ratification
of the Optional Protocol to the Convention on the Rights of the
Child on the Involvement of Children in Armed Conflict at the
United Nations headquarters in New York Friday.
</P>
<P>
Canada was the first member state to sign the Optional Protocol.
</P>
<P>
"I warmly congratulate the government of Canada on this
occasion," Otunnu said.
</P>
<P>
"This development is especially appropriate because Canada has
been playing a very dynamic leadership role in advocating for the
protection of children exposed to abuse and brutalization in
situations of armed conflict," Otunnu said.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to have the Optional Protocol come into force by
the end of this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
To date, eight countries have signed the Optional Protocol. The
treaty comes into force when it has been ratified by 10 members
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Has Right to War Reparation: OAU Panel Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- An international panel
Friday blamed the international community for the failure to stop
the 1994 Rwanda Genocide, saying that the African country should
receive financial reparations from the world community for the
massacre of more than 500,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The Organization of Africa Unity (OAU), in a report released
here Friday, accused the United States, France, Belgium and the U.
N. Security Council of failing to take action to stop the 90-day
genocide when they had the means to do so.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council "members could have prevented the
genocide to take place. They failed to do so," said the committee
in its 318-page report.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "Rwanda: the Preventable Genocide," was
drawn up by seven individuals headed by former Botswana President
Ketumile Masire. The group as formed by the OAU in 1998 to
investigate the causes of the genocide in Rwanda and make
recommendations to avoid the recurrence of such crimes.
</P>
<P>
"In the name of both justice and accountability, reparations
are owed to Rwanda by actors in the international community for
their role before, during and since the genocide," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The genocide was orchestrated by a small group of Hutu
extremists against the Tutsi minority. More than half a million
Tutsi and thousands of moderate Hutus were killed in a slaughter
that ended when Tutsi-led rebels seized control.
</P>
<P>
Hutu extremists killed between 500,000 and 800,000 Tutsi and
opposition Hutus between April and July 1994, said the panel. The
report singled out the United States and France, whose influence
in the Security Council and in Rwanda made them all the more
responsible for the international community's inaction in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"They were in a position to insist that attacks on the Tutsi
must cease, and they chose never to exert that influence," the
report said.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, one of the members of the panel,
Stephen Lewis, who is former Canadian ambassador to the United
Nations, said the U.S. role was a "shame" and reflected badly on U.
S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, the U.S. ambassador to
the United Nations, at the time.
</P>
<P>
"The role of the U.S. at the Security Council, in determinedly
blocking a more effective U.N. intervention force throughout the
entire genocide, is an almost incomprehensible scar of shame on
American foreign policy," Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
"I want to say, as a personal observation, I don't know how
Madeline Albright lives with it," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Has Right to War Reparation, OAU Panel Says  EDS-Updated With U.N. Statement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- An international panel
Friday blamed the international community for the failure to stop
the 1994 Rwanda Genocide, saying that the African country should
receive financial reparations from the world community for the
massacre of more than 500,000 people.
