<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Greece Move to Expand Bilateral Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian and Greek top defense
officials reached here Friday a consensus on a wide range of
international and regional issues and concluded a package of
accords to strengthen their cooperation in the military and
security fields.
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed bilateral relations, particularly in
the fields of defense and arms sales, and European security issues,
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev told the press after a 90-
minute meeting with his Greek counterpart, Apostolos-Athanasios
Tsokhatzopoulos.
</P>
<P>
The two countries hold the same or similar positions on most
international and regional issues, and the security in
Southeastern Europe was given special attention, Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
Tsokhatzopoulos who arrived in Russia Thursday for a two-day
visit, emphasized the need for preserving the 1972 anti-ballistic
missile (ABM) treaty.
</P>
<P>
"The world is not eager to get rid of that treaty," he said.
The development of a so-called tactical ABM system by the United
States would "disturb the world balance," said the Greek minister.
</P>
<P>
Both parties confirmed their interest in maintaining peace and
stability in Southeastern Europe and maintaining intact borders,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries strongly oppose separatist movements and
reiterated the need to fight terrorism, Tsokhatzopoulos said.
</P>
<P>
The talks also covered issues concerning free shipping on the
Mediterranean and Black Seas, and the implementation of various
joint projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Alexei Ogaryov, general director of Russia's
top arms trader Rosvooruzhenie, told reporters that the outlook
for the sale of Russian arms to Greece is "very good."
</P>
<P>
Ogaryov attended a series of the meetings that Tsokhatsopoulos
had in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Rosvooruzhenie supplied Greece with "Osa-AKM"' anti-aircraft
missile systems in 1999, and is now supplying "Zubr" hovercraft-
landing ships under a contract signed in 2000. The company is also
helping with the operation of an "S-300PMU1" anti-aircraft system
and training its Greek crew on the island of Crete.
</P>
<P>
"In light of the successful use of T-80U tanks on Cyprus, we
have a good chance in the current tender to sell this basic tank
to Greece," Ogaryov said.
</P>
<P>
Joint work in modernizing Soviet and Russian defense hardware
owned by Greece is another promising field for cooperation, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Friday, Russian President Vladimir Putin and the Greek
minister exchanged views at the Kremlin on preserving the 1972 ABM
treaty and the setting up of a European ABM system, stressing that
"our views on this issue are similar."
</P>
<P>
Putin noted the importance of "Greek channel" in Russia-NATO
relations, highly evaluating the relations between Russia and
Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
