<HEADLINE> Ugandan House Speaker Calls for Eligible Members for East African Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan National Assembly
Speaker Francis Ayume Friday urged east African countries to elect
knowledgeable members to the Legislative Assembly of the region.
</P>
<P>
"The East African Legislative Assembly should not be used as a
place for off-loading rejects who have failed to perform in their
respective national assemblies," Ayume said at a one-day meeting
of National Assemblies speakers held here Friday.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that people elected to the assembly should have
rich experience with legislative procedures, adding "they should
also have the East African Community at heart."
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, speakers from Uganda, Kenya and the host
Tanzania exchanged views on the implementation of the East African
Community (EAC) Treaty, especially of that of Article 50, which
provides for the election of members of the East African
Legislative Assembly by national parliaments.
</P>
<P>
The article stipulates that elected members should be able to
translate the treaty into laws that could be easily understood by
common people in the region.
</P>
<P>
The meeting on Friday, which was chaired by speaker of the
Tanzanian National Assembly Pius Msekwa, also deliberated the role
of the east African national parliaments in strengthening and
consolidating the integration process in east Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
