<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Envoy Stresses no Change to Blue Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. special envoy to the Middle East
Terje Roed-Larsen stressed here Friday afternoon the U.N.-drawn
Blue Line is "final and will not be changed."
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Lebanese leaders, he told reporters there are
some misunderstandings about the Blue Line, which was established
by the U.N. to verify Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon on May
24.
</P>
<P>
"First of all, I want you to know there is not a concrete
boundary between Lebanon and Israel," he said, adding "U.N. experts
team uses more than 100 maps to set the line. And I also make it
clear that the line is not an international border. It is up to
states to demarcate border."
</P>
<P>
Larsen reiterated the line will not be changed because it is set
just to verify Israel's pullout from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the village of Ghajar that is cut apart by the line,
Larsen said he has not discussed the issue with Lebanese leaders.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official also defended the international body's
neutrality toward the line.
</P>
<P>
"We are not biased or impure in demarcating the line," he said,
asserting "any problems stemming from the process are technical,
not political."
</P>
<P>
After U.N. cartographers drew the Blue Line in June to mark the
border between Israel and Lebanon, local media and Lebanese leaders
accused Larsen of being biased to Israel on the demarcating
process. Beirut also doubts the U.N.'s ability to correct Israel's
encroachments to the Blue Line.
</P>
<P>
U.N. peacekeeping forces reported 12 Israeli violations of the
Blue Line to the Security Council on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Larsen, who arrived in the southern town of Naqoura from Israel
Friday morning, held talks with Lebanese Parliament Speaker Nabih
Berri, President Emile Lahoud and Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
He is due to continue his talks with Lebanese leaders on
Saturday and leave on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
