<HEADLINE> Cyprus Talks to Adjourn on July 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The talks will continue until early August and then resume in
New York from September 12 until early October, spokesman Manoel
De Almeida e Silva quoted Alvaro de Soto, U.N. under-secretary-
general and special adviser to the secretary-general on Cyprus, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. official said the reason for the suspension is "for
consultations."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, an Eastern Mediterranean island country, has been
divided into the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north and the Greek
Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded and
occupied the northern third of the island in the wake of an
abortive pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has tried for decades to reunite the island
but talks between the two communities have so far yielded no
tangible results.
</P>
<P>
Under a renewed call from U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
the latest round of talks between Greek Cypriot leader Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash started in
Geneva on July 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
