<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belarus Sniffs U.S. Suspending Most-Favored-Nation Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Minsk said Friday that Washington's
decision to suspend the Global System of Trade Preferences (GSTP)
in relation to Belarus is not of principal and critical
significance for the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
The GSTP provided for the right to duty-free export of a number
of Belarussian goods to the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
With an average annual trade turnover of 200 million U.S.
dollars between the two countries, the cost of goods that were
subject to the GSTP last year was 26.7 million dollars, and the
preferences themselves did not exceed one million dollars, the
Belarussian Foreign Ministry said Friday
</P>
<P>
"This very sum can be listed among the 'losses' after this
decision comes into force," said the ministry, cited by Russian
news agencies.
</P>
<P>
Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko said Wednesday that
Minsk "will respond to the United States in kind and take
appropriate steps" as regards Washington's decision.
</P>
<P>
By this decision, the United States "deprived Belarus, the
victim of the Chernobyl disaster, of about one million dollars,"
said Lukashenko, proposing to "give that million to (U.S.
President) Bill Clinton to supplement his pension."
</P>
<P>
Clinton Tuesday signed a bill on denying Belarussian exports
duty-free entry onto the U.S. market, initiated by the American
Federation of Labor and Congress of Industrial Organizations (AFL-
CIO) in excuse of "the unsatisfactory labor rights and human
rights situation in Belarus." 
</P>
</TEXT>
