<HEADLINE> Delegates Begin Arriving in S. Africa for AIDS Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- At least 3,000 delegates are
expected to arrive in Durban, South Africa on Friday ahead of the
13th International AIDS Conference which will start in the city on
Sunday, according to Durban International Airport manager Siva
Pillay.
</P>
<P>
Although a 90 million rand (13 million U.S. dollars)
reconstruction project is underway at the airport, delegates
should not be inconvenienced and they would be taken to a special
joint operations center on arrival, where their transport and
baggage would be sorted out, Pillay said.
</P>
<P>
He said SA Airways and British Airways have increased their
number of flights to Durban, or in some cases were using bigger
aircraft to accommodate all the visitors.
</P>
<P>
There are also aircraft of standby in Johannesburg in case of
any emergency, he said, noting that at least four months of
planning has gone into the operation.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the more than 13,000 delegates to the conference,
including over one thousand journalists, are expected to arrive on
Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Security plans have also been put in place to protect delegates
on their way from the airport to their places of accommodation.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of South African Police Services, defense force and
metropolitan police force personnel would be deployed to the
airport, the conference center and places of accommodation, police
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The streets of Durban were on Friday full of armed police and
defense force members patrolling the areas around the
International Convention Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
