<HEADLINE> WFP Short of Funds for Food Aid to Displaced Angolans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The delegation of the World Food
Program (WFP) in Angola is still very poor, with only 42 percent
of the requests for fund having been confirmed by international
donors, said WFP spokeswoman Maria Flynn here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Despite great efforts on getting donations from the
international community, the WFP branch in Angola is far short of
funds for buying food for the increasing displaced Angolans,"
Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
She said the situation has not been improved although it has
recently received a donation of some 12.6 million U.S. dollars
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government has also confirmed a 1.3 million-U.S.
dollar grant, she said.
</P>
<P>
According to Flynn, some 12,000 war-displaced Angolans in the
Osire Camp in Namibia are now living in dire poverty and poor
health.
</P>
<P>
There are currently some 3.7 million war-displaced people in
Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
