<HEADLINE> S. Africa Urged to Meet Challenge of Peace: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- South African President Thabo
Mbeki Friday urged the country to respond seriously to the
challenge of peace and stability on the continent.
</P>
<P>
This is an obligation the country should not shy away from and
South Africans should be willing to help cover the cost of the
country's peacekeeping mission to the Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC), he told reporters in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think we can say considerations about money would
override participation by South Africa in a situation where you
save lives," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It will cost us something," the president said. "As South
Africans, we ought to say we are prepared to pay that."
</P>
<P>
It was revealed last week that South Africa had budgeted 100
million rand (14.7 million U.S. dollars) for a year-long
deployment of specialized military elements in the DRC, which drew
criticism from the opposition.
</P>
<P>
It is quite legitimate for people to be concerned about the
cost, but it would not be correct to "jealously guard" over the
money that would be involved without caring what is happening in
the DRC, Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing happens without expenditure," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
