<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Rate Dips to 4 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. unemployment rate fell
by 0.1 percentage points to 4 percent in June from 4.1 percent the
month before as private-sector hiring outweighed layoffs related
to the winding down of Census 2000, the Labor Department reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Total employment including government workers rose by only 11,
000 in June as 190,000 temporary workers finished work on the
census and left their jobs. That was the weakest growth in four
years.
</P>
<P>
In May, total payrolls rose by 171,000, weaker growth than the
government previously estimated.
</P>
<P>
The private sector added 206,000 jobs last month. In May,
private employers cut 165,000 jobs, compared with the 116,000
decline which was initially reported.
</P>
<P>
Despite the weaker job growth, labor market conditions worsened
during the month as measured by the available pool of labor, an
indicator closely watched by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
The available pool of workers fell 3.4 percent to 9.837 million
workers, a portent that employers could find it increasingly
difficult to fill vacancies in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
Average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures,
rose 0.4 in June to 13.71 U.S. dollars, while the average work
week increased to 34.5 hours compared to 34.4 hours the month
before. Wages grew by a slim 0.1 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has boosted interest rates six times over
the past year to slow the economy and keep inflation under control.
A number of economic reports, including new home sales and retail
sales, have suggested that the Fed's interest rate increases are
working to slow economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Defense Minister Unveils NATO Flying Training Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Minister of National
Defense Art Eggleton opened the NATO Flying Training in Canada (
NFTC) program Thursday in Moose Jaw, Saskatchewan.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony, the minister described the 20-year
NFTC program, which is estimated to cost 3.5 billion Canadian
dollars (about 2.4 billion U.S. dollars), as "one of the most
modern and innovative flying training systems in existence."
</P>
<P>
"NFTC makes a very real and direct contribution to (NATO's)
collective defense capabilities," he said.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Ian Milani, director of the project, indicated the
project could be a redress to criticism by NATO chief George
Robertson last September that Canada failed to keep up with its
NATO commitments.
</P>
<P>
The wide-open skies and superior training facilities available
at bases such as Moose Jaw and Cold Lake, Alberta, will make
Canada an ideal destination for foreign air forces, said Milani.
</P>
<P>
The program, jointly run by Bombardier Aerospace and the
Canadian Forces, has already secured contracts of more than 800
million Canadian dollars (about 538 million U.S. dollars) from
Denmark, Italy, Britain and Singapore, the colonel said.
</P>
<P>
More than 130,000 Allied pilots and aircrew received training
at bases across Canada between 1940 and 1945, with Moose Jaw and
her sister air bases turning out over 1,600 pilots a month,
according to the Canadian military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
