<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> College Entrance Exams Start Amid Expectations (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although the enrollment quota of Chinese colleges has increased
since last year, the examinations remain highly competitive.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, meteorological stations report cool weather;
construction sites are banned from making too much noise to make
sure that students preparing for the exams are not disturbed; and
roads are cleared for examinees' buses.
</P>
<P>
Examination venues are doing what they can to ensure that
examinees are able to do their best. Air-conditioners have been
installed for the first time in the exam rooms in east China's
Nanjing City, which is prone to heatwaves in July.
</P>
<P>
Days ahead of the exam, mass media and websites have published
special editions to help examinees to deal with problems during
the tests.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has been improving a system to subsidize
college students, especially those from poverty-stricken regions.
Every examinee received a pamphlet explaining the relevant policy
before the examination.
</P>
<P>
"The examination is indeed important, but people should
understand that colleges are not the only route to success," said
Qu Zhenyuan, an official with the Ministry of Education. "As China
is building a life-time education system, every person will have
the opportunity to get a better education."  
</P>
</TEXT>
