<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Line Draws Larsen to Middle East Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 7 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Middle East envoy Terje Roed
Larsen arrived in Lebanon Friday to present a modified map of Blue
Line to Lebanese officials to clear up Israel's continuing
violations of the border.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official, accompanied by the U.N.'s chief cartographer
Miklos Pinther, talked with Lebanese leaders on some changes of the
Blue Line drawn by U.N. experts according to the 1923 Lebanese-
Palestinian boundary.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL), which has been deployed
in south Lebanon since 1978 after Israel launched a 90-day war to
Lebanon, reported 12 Israeli violations of the Blue Line to the U.
N. Security Council on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the violations are minor ones, which are mainly
security fences and patrol roads straying north of the Blue Line.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese side has lodged complaints to the U.N., accusing
Israel of deliberate encroachments of the Lebanese territory and
its procrastination of ending the invasion.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss has repeatedly claimed the
government troops will not be deployed unless Israel fulfills an
entire pullout.
</P>
<P>
UNIFIL is reportedly sending patrols along the border every
night to ensure there are no further violations.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Israel on Thursday, Larsen got an assurance
from Prime Minister Ehud Barak that the border violations will end.
But the Israeli leader had vowed to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan last month that the border encroachments would be solved in
three days.
</P>
<P>
While Lebanon objects to the line's differing from the
international border, Israel does not satisfy the U.N. decision.
</P>
<P>
The Blue Line cuts the village of Ghajar into two parts, two-
thirds of it inside Lebanon and the other third within the Israeli-
occupied part of Syria, creating a security nightmare for the
Israeli army.
</P>
<P>
U.N. sources said the new map carried by Pinther shows the Blue
Line more clearly than before and confirmed the Line is "final and
non-negotiable." Some media reported the new map has some changes,
including the delineation of the village of Ghajar.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has taken great pains to emphasize the Blue Line is
simply a line of withdrawal and it is up to Lebanon and Israel to
delineate their mutual boundary.
</P>
<P>
But there has been no convincing explanation from the U.N. as to
why the cartographic team did not base the delineation of the line
on the 1949 Armistice Demarcation Line (ADL).
</P>
<P>
The ADL exactly follows the 1923 boundary except for the last 6
kilometers in the east.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has admitted key documents outlining the border were
destroyed in a flood. The U.N.'s map of the 1949 ADL has gone "
missing". Cartographers defined the Blue Line according to the maps
in the archives of U.N. and from Britain and France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Help Train African Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has pledged to help a number
of African countries train their armed forces staff, reported the
Hurriyet(Freedom) newspaper on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Within the forthcoming eight months, according to the report,
Turkey is expected to sign military cooperation agreements
separately with Burkina Faso, Nigeria, Algeria, Mali, Ghana,
Ethiopia, Chad, Zimbabwe and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
The special project, which is part of Turkey's policy of opening
up to African nations, is a joint initiative being carried out by
the Foreign Ministry and Chief of the General Staff's Office.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Armed Forces (TSK), the second largest army after
that of the United States in NATO, have become a regional training
provider by signing military training and education cooperation
pacts with Israel and Jordan in the Middle East, Azerbaijan and
Georgia in the Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military attaches special importance to cementing
military relations with Jordan and the Turkish-Jordanian military
ties have grown in recent years, coinciding with the increased
military and defense ties between Ankara and Tel Aviv, which
started in 1996 as Israel Aircraft Industry (IAI) won the tender
for upgrading Turkish F-4s.
</P>
<P>
Within the framework of the 1984 Military Training and Education
Cooperation Agreement, Turkey and Jordan have exchanged Cobra
helicopter pilots from the Turkish Land Forces and the Royal
Jordanian Air force.
</P>
<P>
Under a military training agreement with Georgia signed during
former President Suleyman Demirel's visit to Tbilisi at the
beginning of this year, the Turkish Air Force has started to train
Georgian pilots at the Air Force War Academy in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The TSK have also been training Albanian soldiers and are
reportedly preparing to strengthen military cooperation with
Bulgaria in the Balkans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
