<HEADLINE> Bad Loan Ratio Dips Slightly in Philippines in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The non-performing loans of
Philippine commercial banks dipped to 14.41 percent of the total
loans in May from 14.46 percent in April due to a slight increase
in loan portfolio,a senior banker said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"There was a reduction of 0.05 percent from the previous month(
because) there was a slight increase in loans," Central Bank
Governor Rafael Buenaventura told reporters here,
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Buenaventura said the limited recover of the economy
continues to hamper the lending performance of the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the worsening peace and order situation in the
southern part of the country is taking its toll on the economy,
forcing the government to lower its overall economic growth target
for 2000.
</P>
<P>
The government is said to be aiming at only a four percent
growth rate for the gross domestic product (GDP), instead of the
original five percent target.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the GDP growth rate in the first quarter is only 3.5
percent in the Philippines, even below the reduced target of four
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
