<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contraceptive Prevalence Helps Decrease Fertility Rate in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Contraceptive prevalence rate has
increased from merely 8 percent in 1975 to 54 percent among
married women in 1999-2000 in Bangladesh, thus decreasing the
total fertility rate, says a study of the Bangladesh Demographic
Health Survey released Friday.
</P>
<P>
The rate of fertility in Bangladesh has declined to 3.1 percent
for the period 1995-2000 from seven percent between 1970 and 1975,
according to a United Nations Development Program report.
</P>
<P>
In South Asian context, Bangladesh showed a great success in
family planning while fertility rate in Pakistan remains high and
India shows a mixed picture. Family size in Bangladesh declines
steadily by 3.3 percent, said a United Nations Fund for Population
Activities (UNFPA) report.
</P>
<P>
The BDHS study observed that the trend toward smaller families
had been greatly helped by the wider availability of good-quality,
safe and affordable family-planning services, and easier access to
them, especially for women.
</P>
<P>
Pills, by far the most commonly-used method in the country,
have been used by over half (58 percent) of married women both in
urban and rural areas, while injectables, condoms and periodical
abstinence follow one by one.
</P>
<P>
More than three quarters (78 percent) of currently married
women in Bangladesh have had experiences in using family-planning
methods, says the survey report.
</P>
<P>
The study says that the contraceptive use varies in accordance
with women's educational levels. A little more than half of
married women (51 percent) with no formal education used a
contraceptive method, compared with 53 percent of women with
either incomplete or complete primary school education, and 59
percent of those with at least some secondary education. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Streamline Regulation of Financial Advisers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS) will streamline the regulation of financial
advisers and institute a new regime to allow financial
intermediaries to offer an array of financial products and
services under a single license.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Deputy Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong, who doubles
MAS Chairman, made the statement while speaking at the 1st
Anniversary Dinner of the Securities Investors Association of
Singapore (SIAS) Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
He said the MAS will draw up legislation to regulate financial
intermediaries and to promote emergence of a single class of
independent advisors who can offer comprehensive financial
planning and advice on the entire range of investment options.
</P>
<P>
Under the current regulation, financial advisers who wish to
provide advice and distribute different financial products have to
be licensed or registered, or both, under different statutes.
</P>
<P>
Lee said there are significant advantages to consolidating the
legislation regulating personal financial advice, adding a single
license for all financial advisers will complement the single
license that MAS will be introducing for all securities
intermediaries such as stockbrokers, futures traders, or fund
managers, who deal in securities or manage client funds.
</P>
<P>
According to Lee, the model of a single license would establish
a consistent set of regulatory requirements, allow uniform
professional standards to be maintained and encourage the
emergence of personal financial intermediaries as a class of
financial intermediaries who provide financial advice regardless
of the type of investment products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
