<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. legal Team Leaves Cambodia After Successful Talks on Trial Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations legal team
led by Hans Corell left Cambodia Friday after concluding their
successful talks on setting up a special court with foreign
participation to bring former Khmer Rouge leaders to trial.
</P>
<P>
The talks were conducted between Hans Corell, U.N.
undersecretary general for legal affairs, and his counterpart Sok
An, Cambodia's chief negotiator and chairman of the Council of
Ministers.
</P>
<P>
Both team leaders confirmed that the negotiations on the trial
issue were finalized while the next step is to go further on
administrative and technical procedures including a debate at
Cambodia's parliament.
</P>
<P>
``It is now the responsibility of the government to ensure that
the parliament passes the draft law in timely fashion in a form
that is in keeping with the understanding we have reached as a
result of our talks,'' said Hans Corell before his departure to
New York.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had presented a draft of memorandum of
understanding to Sok An that would govern mutual cooperation and
operation of the court.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have agreed Cambodia will select three of its judges
and the United Nations will select two foreign judges to sit on a
panel to rule on the indictment disputes.
</P>
<P>
After the successful negotiations, a Memorandum of the
Understanding would be singed by the United Nations and Cambodia
if the Cambodian parliament passes legislation that is in keeping
with the understanding reached between the two parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
