<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore to Set up Rigid Disclosure Requirements for Listed Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at the 1st anniversary dinner of the Securities
Investors Association of Singapore (SIAS), Singapore Deputy Prime
Minister Lee Hsien Loong, who is concurrently MAS chairman, said
that a committee charged with reviewing Corporate Regulation and
Governance Policy will review and change Singapore's disclosure
requirements and practices to ensure that full and prompt
disclosure of material information be reported by listed companies.
.
</P>
<P>
"Listed companies must establish high standards of reporting
and disclosure, " Lee emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He said: "We also intend to change the law to make continuous
disclosure by listed companies a statutory obligation."
</P>
<P>
"This means that non-disclosure or late disclosure of material
information will be a breach of the law that will carry a judicial
penalty, and not just be a breach of Singapore Exchange's listing
requirements," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lee holds that the Singapore Exchange has the duty to make sure
that companies release corporate news and financial results
promptly and fully.
</P>
<P>
"Companies should make full and prompt disclosure a major
corporate priority," he said, noting "This is not just because
disclosure is an exchange or legal requirement, but because it is
the companies' responsibility to shareholders."
</P>
<P>
"Disclosure and transparency are essential to good corporate
governance," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
