</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. National Transportation Safety Board said Thursday
that John F. Kennedy Jr. lost control of the single-engine plane
he was flying last year, leading to the crash that killed him, his
wife and her sister.
</P>
<P>
-- After years of industrial and financial malaise, political
gridlock and government indecision, Russia has adopted the most
liberal market-oriented economic program attempted since the
collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. government is planning to postpone the first
federal execution in nearly 40 years because of the absence of
clemency procedures and concerns about racial and geographic
disparities in death penalty cases.
</P>
<P>
-- The Yugoslav Parliament Thursday approved constitutional
changes that would let President Slobodan Milosevic run for a new
term next year and that diminish the influence of Montenegro,
Serbia's small sister republic.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. Commerce Department said Thursday that new orders
to U.S. factories rose 4.1 percent in May, the largest increase
since the end of 1992.
</P>
<P>
-- Northern Ireland authorities Thursday banned a second
Protestant parade amid violence that followed the blocking of an
earlier march through a Catholic area. Clashes continued in
Belfast, where British troops are on patrol, and in the flashpoint
town of Drumcree. 
