<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Inquiry into Voting Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The South African bid
committee announced on Friday that they would launch an
independent inquiry into the voting process which handed the 2006
World Cup to Germany.
</P>
<P>
Irvin Khoza, president of the bid committee, said committee
member Michael Katz would conduct a thorough investigation into
the abstention from voting by New Zealander Charles Dempsey, the
Oceania Football Confederation representative on the FIFA
executive, and purported shady deals before the actual voting.
</P>
<P>
Dempsey's failure to vote sank South Africa's chance of hosting
the 2006 World Cup and handed the bid to Germany.
</P>
<P>
Bid leader Danny Jordaan, Khoza and the South African Football
Association (SAFA) president Molefi Olifant refused to answer
questions pertaining to any bribery allegations against Dempsey,
saying they would make a statement only after the evaluation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his arrival in South Africa, Jordaan made it
clear that South Africa would be in contention for the 2010 cup
despite striking an 11th hour deal with Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Jordaan said the condition of that deal was that South Africa
would only back Brazil in 2010 had they won the rights to host the
2006 World Cup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
