<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African President Writes to NZ PM over Bid Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 7 (Xinhua) -- President Thabo Mbeki wrote to
New Zealand premier Helen Clark on Thursday, reaffirming the close
ties between their two countries despite the key role a Kiwi
played in wrecking South Africa 2006 soccer World Cup bid.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki thanked Prime Minister Clark and her government for the
support they gave the South African bid in the run-up to the
crucial vote in Zurich on Thursday, Mbeki's spokeswoman Tasneem
Carrim said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his confidence that the support Clark had
expressed for South Africa's bid genuinely reflected her view and
that of the people of New Zealand as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Germany beat South Africa to host the tournament by 12 votes to
11 when Oceania soccer chief Charlie Dempsey abstained from the
third round of voting.
</P>
<P>
The Scots-born New Zealander appeared to defy instructions of
his own federation and the New Zealand government to vote for
South Africa if England were knocked out of the voting.
</P>
<P>
FIFA officials said it appeared that Dempsey had withdrawn his
vote for "personal reasons".
</P>
<P>
On Friday, New Zealand Sports Minister Trevor Mallard branded
Dempsey, "an international embarassment" and expressed fears that
his actions had damaged the international reputation of the entire
country".
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, however, said he was confident that Dempsey's actions
were contrary to Clark's view, that of her government and the New
Zealand people.
</P>
<P>
As much as the people of South Africa and the rest of Africa
deplored Dempsey's decision, Mbeki assured Clark that she and the
people of New Zealand are genuine friends of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki assured the people of New Zealand that their relations
with South Africa would in no way be harmed by the actions of a
member of the FIFA executive, over which they had no control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
