<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Lanka's Opposition Tables Motion of Non-confidence Against Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaker Ratnayake on Thursday allowed UNP's Ronnie De Mel to
wind up the emergency debate although the party had listed Rajitha
Senaratna as its last speaker, said a UNP official while
explaining the party's motion.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, former finance minister Ronnie De Mel broke a
party decision and announced that he would vote with the
government to extend a national emergency, effectively crossing-
over to the ruling People's Alliance (PA).
</P>
<P>
Ronnie De Mel's decision was a major blow to the UNP. He became
the seventh UNP parliamentarian to support the PA in recent times.
Last year five UNP lawmakers crossed over to the government and
another one followed suit last week.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that several more UNP parliamentarians were
planning to cross over to the government side to help it get a two-
thirds majority in the 225-member Parliament needed to pass its
constitutional reforms aimed at ending the long ethnic conflict.
</P>
<P>
The proposed reforms aim to devolve more powers to regions,
including one administered by Tamils, in an effort to wean the
minority away from Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) rebels
who have been fighting for a separate homeland called Eelam in Sri
Lanka's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The PA government and the UNP are due to end the bipartisan
talks on the draft constitution on Friday with the UNP saying all
outstanding issues have not been discussed.
</P>
<P>
President Kumaratunga has said that she would introduce the new
constitution to Parliament by the third week of this month.
</P>
<P>
However, constitutional experts said the new constitution needs
to be approved by a two-thirds majority in Parliament and approved
at a referendum. They said since Parliament will have to be
dissolved in the third week of August, there would not be enough
time to complete the entire process.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE have rejected the constitutional proposals, saying the
separatist war will continue as the package fails to address the
issue of Tamil self-determination.
</P>
<P>
Parliament on Thursday extended the national emergency by a
month amid uproar with the UNP opposing the measure complaining
certain procedural lapses in it.
</P>
<P>
The emergency gives sweeping powers to security forces to
arrest LTTE suspects. As per the regulations, the emergency has to
be extended by parliament every month and the UNP till now had
abstained every month whenever the bill on extending emergency
provision by one month came for the approval in Parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Recruit Women in Battle Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At present women are only allowed in the medical units as
doctors and nurses.
</P>
<P>
An advertisement in local daily newspapers Friday announced the
government is going to recruit women cadets for the 47th Long
Course for two years' training in Bangladesh Military Academy (BMA)
, the spokesman said, adding that the Air Force and the Navy last
year recruited some women only for "specialized trade," but the
Army is going to recruit females in its regular service.
</P>
<P>
Female students under 21 years who have acquired the Higher
Secondary Certificate (HSC) are eligible to apply for the female
cadets, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Labeling the new recruitment strategy "epoch-making," the
advertisement called for the women to join the Army.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh armed forces have more than 100,000 members at
present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
