<HEADLINE> FIFA: Dempsey Receives Death Threat before Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- FIFA said Friday that New Zealand's
Charles Dempsey, the delegate whose abstention effectively handed
the 2006 World Cup finals to Germany, had earlier received a death
threat.
</P>
<P>
In a Thursday's executive committee meeting in Zurich, Dempsey
had said that he and his family had been threatened, FIFA
spokesman Keith Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
"Charlie referred at the beginning of the meeting to legal
advice which he had taken because of the difficult personal
situation he found himself in," Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said he "absolutely subscribe to the description
of intolerable unbearable personal pressure".
</P>
<P>
Asked if the manner of the pressure means death threats, he
said: "If you want to interpret it that way I would not disagree
with it."
</P>
<P>
Dempsey abstained in the third and final vote, after plumping
for England in the first two rounds. It meant that Germany won the
vote 12-11, ending favourite South Africa's hopes of staging the
tournament. 
</P>
</TEXT>
