<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Storms Claim 25 lives in N. Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The torrential rains and heavy winds
brought by Typhoon Edeng have left 25 people dead and destroyed
crops and infrastructure amounting to 120 million pesos (3 million
U.S. dollars), the government said Friday.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the National Disaster Coordinating Council (
NDCC) said the calamity also left five people injured, 10 others
missing, and some 120,000 families displaced.
</P>
<P>
The entire province of Pampanga in central Luzon has been
placed under a state of calamity after heavy rains submerged two-
thirds of the area in floodwaters, the NDCC said.
</P>
<P>
Other reports said the hardest hit is Guagua city in Bataan
province, where waters rose to as high as six feet, or about 1.8
meters deep.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC pointed out Bulacan also in Bataan province was the
worst hit by the calamity with loses in agriculture amounting to
70 million pesos (1.75 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it placed the value of damaged roads and bridges in
Pangasinan at 19.7 million pesos (492,000 dollars), while damaged
properties in Ilocos Sur were estimated at 12 million pesos (300,
000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
But the government said this should not be a cause for alarm
since the typhoon is already on its way out of the country, and
that water levels in several parts of the country have began to
subside.
</P>
<P>
NDCC Chairman Orlando Mercado, who is also defense secretary,
said the NDCC, along with local government units, have been coping
with the rising number of evacuees.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC said it has set up 44 evacuation centers for the
displaced families and relief operations are now in full swing.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, being reportedly on the typhoon belt,
experiences an average of 19 storms every year from June to
December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Killed, 3 Injured in Bomb Blast in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 7 (Xinhua) -- One person was killed and three
others injured including a woman when a bomb ripped through a
parked wagon in Lahore on Friday, the Associated Press of Pakistan
(APP) reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the police, the bomb was planted under a seat of a
Mazda Wagon which was parked at Badami Bagh General Bus Station.
There was no passenger in the wagon when the explosion occurred
Friday afternoon but the blast was so powerful that four passers-
by were injured, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The injured were rushed to the hospital where one of them named
Anwar succumbed to his wounds, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
