<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Health Sector Hindered by Severe Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7(Xinhua) -- The Rwanda health sector still faces
severe problems including insufficiency of qualified health
personnel and lack of medical facilities and fund, Rwanda News
Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Following the tragic events that befell Rwanda in 1994, the
efficiency of health services was drastically affected because of
shortage of qualified medical personnel and poor health care in
general," Health Minister Ezechias Rwabuhihi was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the government policy on health encourages the
establishment of training institutions to promote health through
education with particular emphasis on human resource development.
</P>
<P>
Some half million Rwandans, including Tutsis and moderate
Hutus, were killed in the genocide in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thomas Karengera, director of health care in the
Ministry of Health, said the orientation of the national health
policy is the development of primary health and decentralization
of medical facilitates to cover the entire community.
</P>
<P>
"There is, however, need for human resource development,
increased health information, improvement of collaboration
between the health and education sectors, development of
information technology and liasing with similar organizations on
the national and international levels," Karengera stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
