<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Dismisses Letter Offering Bribes "Hoax" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The letter offering bribes to FIFA
delegates for votes in favor of Germany's bid for the 2006 World
Cup finals was a hoax, said Germany's soccer federation (DFB) on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the vote up to 10 members of the 24-member FIFA
executive committee had reportedly received the letter under their
hotel doors.
</P>
<P>
The letter was signed by Martin Hansen, who claimed to be
secretary TDES (WM 2006 initiative) and said it was written on
behalf of the German bid chief Franz Beckenbauer.
</P>
<P>
But DFB spokesman Wolfgang Niersbach said that the person named
does not belong to their organisation.
</P>
<P>
"The whole situation is mysterious," Niersbach told Germany's
SID sports news agency.
</P>
<P>
FIFA press spokesman Keith Cooper also said that they were not
taking the hoax seriously.
</P>
<P>
"The whole thing is done so stupidly and in such an amateur
fashion that we don't want to give the issue any more meaning than
it deserves," Cooper told SID.
</P>
<P>
Germany won the vote 12-11 after New Zealander Charles Dempsey,
representing Oceania, abstained. Dempsey, 78, was among the
delegates who received the letter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
