<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nadam Festival Opens in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A grand-scale festival, called "
Nadam" in Mongolian, was held today at the grasslands of the Hulun
Buir League in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Nadam, which means "entertainment and games" in Mongolian, has
a tradition of more than 700 years. Throughout the history of the
event, horse racing, archery and Mongolian wrestling have been
three major activities.
</P>
<P>
Track and field events, ball sports, art performances and photo
shows are also included in this year's Nadam, which was jointly
sponsored by the autonomous regional tourism bureau and government
of Hulun Buir league, said a local tourism official.
</P>
<P>
Such fairs are normally held throughout the grasslands in
summer or autumn seasons when flowers are blooming, the grass is
green, and the cattle and sheep are well-fed.
</P>
<P>
Cheered on by the audience, a team gave an outstanding
performance at today's opening ceremony. Wrestling, horse racing,
and archery competitions followed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Launch of China's Smallest Satellite Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- China's smallest satellite,
launched a week ago, has basically finished its testing mission
and is now working well, an official of the Astronautics Research
Center of Qinghua University said here today.
</P>
<P>
This means that some universities, research institutes and
corporations may set foot in this field before long, ending the
monopoly of governmental departments, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The mini-satellite, named "Aerospace Qinghua No.1," was put
into space orbit on June 28 at Russia's Plesetsk Cosmodrome by a
Russian carrier rocket. It soon entered its scheduled sun-
synchronous orbit 700 km away from the earth.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, weighing about 50 kg and measuring 0.07 cubic
meter, took research staff one year and cost some 100 million yuan
(about 12 million U.S. dollars) to develop.
</P>
<P>
"Mini-satellites make it possible for universities to
participate in aerospace research and development," said Xu Xin,
senior engineer with the Center.
</P>
<P>
According to Xu, large and expensive satellites may eventually
be replaced by low-cost mini-satellites weighing less than 100 kg.
"It is a similar revolution to the one which replaced most
mainframe computers with personal computers in the world market,"
Xu said.
</P>
<P>
The world's smallest satellite only weighs a few hundred grams,
and the "Aerospace Qinghua No.1" is the lightest one in China.
</P>
<P>
It is the joint achievement of the China Aerospace
Electromechanical Group, Qinghua University and Britain's
University of Surrey. Qinghua sent ten research staff members to
the University of Surrey for study and cooperation in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will be involved in the latest scientific
experiments in aerospace and communications technologies, and then
serve commercial clients. It might later be used for disaster
monitoring, navigation, communications and military purposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese T-bond Market Weekly Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese treasury bonds extended the
narrow fluctuations this week, according to Homeway, China's
leading on-line financial and securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
Three comparatively old bonds closed down 0.28 yuan on average
while the three bonds listed after 1999 picked up by 0.23 yuan in
the average price. The repurchasing transaction highlighted the
market this week with very active turnover.
</P>
<P>
Bond 009905 (3.28 percent, due 2007) and 009908 (3.30 percent,
due 2009) rebounded by 0.21 yuan and 0.15 yuan respectively
following their over drops last week. In contrast, the old bonds
were brought down by 009704, a 9.78 percent bond due 2007, which
dipped 0.39 yuan for the week. Bond 000896 (8.56 percent, due 2003)
and 000696 (11.83 percent, due 2006) lost 0.28 yuan and 0.16 yuan
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Bond 010004, the bond listed this year with a floating interest
rate, has halted correction and risen close to the record high of
102.04 yuan, which it made on June 28. The bond kept moving upward
with active turnover since its debut, attracting a host of bond
investors.
</P>
<P>
As the third quarter of this year has started, securities
investment funds are selling treasuries and moving their capitals
back into the bullish stock market, leaving the T-bond trade thin.
</P>
<P>
There are a number of IPOs early this week, which greatly
affected the money supply and demand on the market. And the tight
money supply in turn impelled the repo transactions. The interest
rate on three-day and seven-day transactions briefly touched 12
percent and 10 percent respectively. On the whole, the interest
rate on China's repo market seems to be on an upward trend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen A Shares Linger This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Shenzhen composite index slid 0.
41 points to 601.65 points on Friday. The sub-index ended at 4751.
99 points, down 78.68 points or 1.6 percent from last Friday's
close of 4830.67 points.
</P>
<P>
According to Homeway, China's leading on-line financial and
securities advisory company, the Shenzhen market's week-long
turnover stood at 47.59 billion yuan (5.73 billion US dollars),
which was 33.22 percent less than that of last week's 71.27
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, the Shenzhen stock market index turned down
due to the IPO pressure and investors' concern about listed
companies' interim results.
</P>
<P>
From Monday to Friday, over 600 million shares of 11 new A
stocks were issued online through the Shanghai and Shenzhen stock
exchanges and eight transferred rights stocks worth 4.037 billion
yuan of market value were listed on the Shanghai Stock Exchange on
Monday. The move attracted a large amount of capital from the
secondary market.
</P>
<P>
In addition, as four new A stocks were listed on the two
bourses this week, the number of China's listed companies exceeds
1,000 and totals 1,004. And the number of listed stocks totals 1,
086.
</P>
<P>
After 43 companies announced their expected losses, the first
listed company's interim report was released on Friday by Lanzhou
Minbei Share-holding (Group) Co. Ltd. The company's profit was 9.
277 million yuan in the first half of this year, of which 300
million yuan was earned from its investment income. The company's
earning per share was 0.079 yuan.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, to further implement the Provisional Methods on
Listed Companies' Share Placement to the Public, China Securities
Regulatory Commission (CSRC) requests securities companies, which
are qualified to be leading underwriters, to strengthen the
internal co-ordination and staff training in order to make
preparation for the additional share issuance. The policy will
slow the market expansion in the near term.
</P>
<P>
Also it was reported today that China's stock market soared 47
percent in the first half of 2000, becoming the best global
performer, according to the Wall Street investment firm Merrill
Lynch. The good news will stimulate the stock market to a new high
next week, Homeway analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
