<HEADLINE> Shenzhen B Share Market Weekly Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Shenzhen B-share market index
plunged 4.25 points, or 3.70 percent, to 110.49 points this week.
</P>
<P>
According to Homeway, China's leading on-line financial and
securities advisory company, turnover was 438.26 million HK
dollars (464.56 million yuan), 63.26 million HK dollars or 12.61
percent less than the total of last week.
</P>
<P>
The loss forecast from over 30 stocks so far weighed on the
broader market for most of the time amid speculation that more
companies will soon be issuing warnings of corporate losses.
Negative announcements had been running a little high.
</P>
<P>
The most steep losses came on concerns of market expansion.
Foshan Huanxin Packaging Co. Ltd debut on the Shenzhen Stock
Exchange on Thursday amid investor enthusiasm for the first new
issue of B shares in two years on the exchange.
</P>
<P>
The company's successful listing helped lift investors'
interest in two other initial share sales by Chinese companies,
which was in the meantime draining money from those already-listed
shares and left the door open to a rather steep downward move in
the market.
</P>
<P>
The market did stabilize before the weekend as thoughts of the
accelerating reforms in China's stock market helped the markets to
recover from the session lows.
</P>
<P>
China will encourage foreign-invested companies to seek listing
either on the yuan-denominated A-share market or the foreign
currency B-share market. And the nation's securities regulator is
considering a proposal to let companies that already trade their
stocks as H shares in Hong Kong sell A shares.
</P>
<P>
Also, technically, the ability to quickly recover back above
the lows had also sparked some buying interest despite the still
negative inclination.
</P>
<P>
Gains will not be overtly aggressive next week, given the
numerous earning warnings and negative comments. The market
performance is not likely to be very impressive for a period of
time, Homeway analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
