<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Westerners Concerned with Turkey's Verdict on Former PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Western countries, the European Union
(EU) in particular, are concerned with the one-year jail term and
lifelong political ban slapped on pro-Islamic former Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan, Turkish Daily News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement on Thursday, the Parliamentary Assembly
of the Council of Europe said the conviction, which came at a time
when EU Commissioner for Enlargement Guenter Verheugen will visit
Ankara next week, was a threat to Turkey's efforts for EU
membership.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Appeals Court Wednesday upheld the one-year jail term
handed down to Erbakan, 74, in March. Diplomatic sources said that
Verheugen will certainly touch upon the matter during his visit.
</P>
<P>
Although the EU, still waiting for the final conclusion of the
legal procedure, has not yet issued a written statement on the
case, its officials have expressed dissatisfaction with the
conviction.
</P>
<P>
EU diplomats in Ankara said the life-time political ban on
Erbakan will affect Turkey's bid for EU membership "negatively."
</P>
<P>
French Ambassador in Ankara Bernard Garcia, whose country has
assumed the EU presidency for the second half of 2000, said that as
an EU candidate, Turkey should make "necessary political reforms"
to improve human rights.
</P>
<P>
If reforms regarding freedom of speech are carried out, Garcia
said, cases like Erbakan's will not take place in the future.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan was found guilty by the Diyarbakir State Security Court
of "inciting hatred and animosity among people on the basis of
racial, religious and social class differences," during a speech in
eastern Bingol province on February 25, 1994.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, leader of the Islamic Welfare Party who became Turkey's
first Islamic prime minister in June 1996, was forced to resign one
year later under heavy pressures from the powerful military, a
staunch defender of secularism.
</P>
<P>
In January 1998, the Constitutional Court ordered the closure of
Welfare Party for violation of secularism stipulated in the
constitution. Erbakan and other leaders of the party were banned
from politics for a period of five years.
</P>
<P>
Although predominantly Muslim, Turkey has adopted a strict
secular political regime and kept an vigilant eye on the influence
of Islamic parties.
</P>
<P>
By law, Erbakan still has a final recourse before the sentence
is implemented.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Richard Boucher on Wednesday
also accused Erbakan's indictment as a violation of freedom of
speech.
</P>
<P>
The United States made similar reactions when former pro-Islamic
Istanbul mayor Recep Tayyip Erdogan was convicted and sent to jail
in 1998 on the same charge.
</P>
<P>
Western diplomatic sources said the EU hopes a solution could be
found for Erbakan's case to the effect that he would not be put
behind bars.
</P>
<P>
The EU has also warned against the possible closure of pro-
Islamic opposition Virtue Party, which was accused of being
successor to the outlawed Welfare Party.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the EU has debated whether to issue a
diplomatic protest if the Turkish Constitutional Court decides to
close the Virtue Party in its pending trial.
</P>
<P>
Some Western diplomats said that in case of a closure decision,
Turkey's EU membership will be delayed for at least one year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Dead, 34 Injured in Earthquake in Istanbul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A woman died of heart attack and 34
people were slightly injured leaping from windows and balconies in
panic when an earthquake measuring 4.2 on the Richter scale jolted
Turkey's biggest city Istanbul at 3.15 a.m. local time (0115 GMT)
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old woman, residing on the fourth floor of an
apartment in Gebze district of the city, had a heart stroke and
died when her husband rushed her to a nearby hospital, Anatolia
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Istanbul-based Bogazici University Kandilli Observatory and
Seismology Center said that the epicenter of the tremor was at the
islands in the Marmara Sea more than 30 kilometers south of
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the mild quake was an independent one and was not
an aftershock of the two strong earthquakes which hit the country
last year at Marmara region and northwestern Bolu province
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Turkish officials said there was no damage to the buildings due
to the quake.
</P>
<P>
Quake-prone Turkey suffered two devastating earthquakes last
year, claiming nearly 20,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
