<HEADLINE> FIFA to Investigate Bribery Attempt Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- World soccer's governing body Friday
said in Zurich it would launch an inquiry into an apparent attempt
to bribe its members before the vote for the 2006 World Cup, but
would not yet call in the police.
</P>
<P>
FIFA spokesman Andreas Herren said: "I can confirm that FIFA
and the German football association will both conduct their own
investigations before going to other authorities."
</P>
<P>
It was revealed Thursday that a number of executive committee
members of the FIFA executive committee had received a letter --
purporting to be from the German bidders -- offering gifts in
return for votes for Germany.
</P>
<P>
Germany beat South Africa in the contest to host the 2006 World
Cup finals by 12 votes to 11 after the Oceania delegate, Charles
Dempsey of New Zealand, abstained in the final round of voting.
</P>
<P>
FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper said Thursday the letter had not
worried those who had received it.
</P>
<P>
Cooper said:"The feeling of those members of the committee who
received this letter purporting to be from a member of one of the
bidding committees was that it was not to be taken seriously."
</P>
</TEXT>
