<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed higher on the
Singapore Stock Market Friday on the back of investors' selective
buying of banking and blue chip issues.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) ended up 27.88 points
to end at 2,092.63 points, or 1.4 percent, in active trading.
</P>
<P>
The total volume surged to 605.63 million units valued at 790.
80 million Singapore dollars (about 457.11 million U.S. dollars).
Gainers outpaced losers by 250 to 91 with 209 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
MediaRng was the most heavily traded stock with a turnover of
64.10 million shares. It was followed by Shining with a volume of
34.12 million units. PKTech was the next with 26.34 million
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Chartered led the ascent of the day rising up 80 cents to close
at 15.50 Singapore dollars. Creative 50 gained 60 cents to finish
at 40.20 Singapore dollars. OCBC, PacCent, SPH, UOB and Venture
each moved up 30 cents to end at 12.40, 20.60, 27.60, 11.60 and 18.
10 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
DBS topped the losers chart slipping by 80 cents to close at 22.
50 Singapore dollars. Datacrft and SembLog gave up 35 cents to
finish at 7.90 and 9.60 Singapore dollars separately. SIA 200
edged down 20 cents to end at 17.80 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealer said sentiment was upbeat following the overnight gains
on Nasdaq, but small issues and newly-listed stocks continued to
dominate trading activity.
</P>
<P>
Technology and electronics counters also recovered some losses
incurred during the last lackluster trading days when some
analysts indicated signs of a slowdown in demand for computer
chips.
</P>
<P>
SPH (Singapore Press Holdings) rose after the group announced
plans to raise advertising rates for its three newly redesigned
newspapers in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
