<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Moon to be Visible July 16: Astronomers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese astronomers say that as
long as the night of July 16 is clear, people in many parts of
China will have the chance to watch the Moon turn red and a comet
streak through the sky.
</P>
<P>
Li Enjie, an expert with the Beijing Planetarium, said the Red
Moon is caused by the refraction of red sunlight in the atmosphere
during a total lunar eclipse.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Sichao, a research fellow at the Purple
Mountain Observatory, the lunar eclipse is expected to last nearly
four hours, the longest in a century.
</P>
<P>
He said it will begin at 7:57 p.m. (Beijing Time). A total
lunar eclipse will start at 9:02 p.m. and the eclipse will enter
its final phase at 11:54 p.m.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the trail of the comet Linear will be visible to the
naked eye that night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
