<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Killer Litter Offenders' Flats Confiscated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Three Singaporeans convicted of
throwing litters from high rise buildings are set to lose their
own houses.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's Housing Board is taking back three flats where the
occupiers had recently been convicted of killer litter offenses,
according to a news report Friday by the local Channel News Asia.
</P>
<P>
The three people were convicted in May for three separate
killer litter offenses, that is, the throwing of empty beer
bottles, the throwing of durian husks, and the throwing of plastic
container and three glasses from their respective high buildings.
</P>
<P>
In Singapore, anyone convicted of causing death by a rash act,
such as throwing killer litter, faces a two-year jail term or a
fine or both.
</P>
<P>
Besides, under the Housing and Development Board ( HDB) Act,
the authorities can also acquire the flat if the person staying in
the flat is convicted of throwing killer litter. The offenders
will also be barred from buying or renting a HDB flat for five
years.
</P>
<P>
The Singaporeans' concern over the threat of litters falling
from high buildings heightened recently after a 5-year-old girl
was killed in April by a flower pot which fell on her as she was
walking at the foot of an HDB block.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers carried articles condemning the act of killer
littering and calling for tougher penalties on the offenders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto's House Arrest Status Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesia's Attorney General
Office (AGO) has extended again, for the fourth time, the house
arrest status of former President Soeharto until August 10, a
report said Friday.
</P>
<P>
It said that the extension of the status is the final one, and
based on the country's crime code, after that, the status could
not be extended any longer.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Soeharto's lawyer Juan Felix Tampubolon confirmed
the extension of the Soeharto's house arrest status, adding that
prosecutors of the AGO will also examine his client.
</P>
<P>
"This morning, I was contacted by the AGO," Tampubolon was
quoted by Suara Pembaruan daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was suspected of abusing power and authority by
issuing decrees and government regulations to amass funds through
seven tax-free charity foundations he set up and chaired during
his 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
He has been put under house arrest and was banned from leaving
the country since in May.
</P>
<P>
The AGO has pledged to try Soeharto before August 10 this year,
or before the country's law making body of the People's
Consultatives Assembly (MPR) hold its annual session scheduled for
August 7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
