<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Unveils Bidders for Telkom Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has unveiled
six pre- qualified firms that had applied for the 49 percent stake
in Telkom Kenya, the former sole state-owned telecommunication
company in the country.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the pre-qualified firms, Kenyan Finance Minister
Chris Okemo said here Thursday that the final winner would be
known by the end of October this year, Kenya's major newspapers
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The six companies are German giant Deutsche Telcom, South
African mobile operator MTN, Egypt's Orascom, British Telecom,
Malaysia Telecom and the Mount Kenya Communications consortium.
</P>
<P>
Okemo said the sale of the 49 percent stake in Telkom Kenya is
part of the government's efforts to liberalize the country's
telecommunications sector.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the bidders would now have an opportunity to
carry out their own audit which involves reviewing the
information on Telkom's operations and talks with the company
management over next eight to 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here hope the move will reduce telephone service fees,
some of the highest on the continent, and place Kenya at par with
its East African neighbors.
</P>
<P>
About 100 Kenyans share one telephone line in the country,
while the figures for South Africa and Mauritius are 11.5 and 21.4
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
