<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Harvest More Grain in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The gross grain crop in Russia will
reach 65-67 million tons this year, up 10-12 million tons from
1999, Russian Deputy Prime Minister, Agriculture Minister Alexei
Gordeyev said in a latest report to the parliament, according to
media reports Friday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 90,000 hectares have been harvested by the end of
June, the harvest averaging 3.8 metric tons per hectare, better
than last year. The fodder crop harvest has risen 36 percent over
last year, Gordeyev said.
</P>
<P>
Russia produced 54.7 million tons of grain in 1999, compared to
47.8 million tons in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The need for fodder grain will not be fully met, considering
that last year's grain reserves are limited," said Gordeyev,
urging the creation of strategic grain reserve funds at the
federal and regional levels.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency cited Russia's Grain Union president
Alexander Yukish as saying that Russia will have to import 6-10
million tons of grain in 2001 to meet its food shortage.
</P>
<P>
According to the Grain Union, grain reserves in the country now
amount to about 8 million tons, and transitional reserves as of
July 1, 2000 will be kept at 2-3 million tons. Annual grain
consumption in Russia is estimated at 75 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
