<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Agencies Agree on New Approach to Help Poor Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Six international agencies have
agreed on new arrangements to help the 48 United Nations
designated least-developed countries (LDCs) integrate more
effectively into the global economy, according to a press release
by the World Trade Organization (WTO) here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We have a responsibility, shared with governments and other
agencies and institutions, to do better in assisting the LDCs to
integrate into the world economy," said WTO Director-General Mike
Moore at a meeting of heads and representatives of the six
organizations held Thursday in New York.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, it is the LDC governments themselves that must
determine their policies and priorities, but we must be ready to
give them effective help. It is time these countries see more of
the positive side of globalization," said the WTO chief, who
chaired the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The new arrangements lay considerable stress on ensuring that
trade policy, trade-related technical assistance, and capacity-
building needs are articulated in a broad development context. The
heads of the agencies firmly shared the view held by most
governments and the development community at large, that these
aspects of policy simply cannot be addressed in isolation, said
the release.
</P>
<P>
The International Trade Center, the International Monetary Fund,
the U.N. Development Program, the U.N. Conference for Trade and
Development, the World Bank, and the WTO established the
Integrated Framework for trade-related technical assistance to
LDCs three years ago as a cooperative inter-agency effort to help
the poorest countries integrate more effectively into the global
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
