<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Part of Belgians Can Opt for Work of Four-day Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 7 (Xinhua) -- From now on, Flemish civil
servants in Belgium can opt for work of a 38-hour, four-day week,
as a new collective labor agreement was signed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Local media said Friday that the flexible working hours for
Flemish civil servants will in the future run from 7:30 a.m. to 7:
00 p.m., which makes trial periods for a four-day working week
possible in this bilingual country.
</P>
<P>
The main official languages in Belgium are French and Flemish.
French-speaking Belgians and Flemish-speaking Belgians usually
live in two different regions -- Wallon and Flanders. Under the
law, they have different rights in certain aspects.
</P>
<P>
In Belgium, civil servants divide into two parts: Flemish civil
servants and French civil servants. All levels of the government
in this country include the two kinds of servants. Therefore,
employment policy for different groups are not same.
</P>
<P>
For the four-day and 38-hour working week, trade unions first
opposed as they wanted a shorter working week, but most union
members wanted the possibility to stay home for at least one more
day.
</P>
<P>
The flexible working hours will allegedly make it easier to
combine work and family life and also help people to avoid the
rush hours. It will permit the Flemish citizens to use the Flemish
services outside the usual office hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
