<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
national news Xinhua released from July 1 to 7:
</P>
<P>
-- Schools run by the Communist Party of China (CPC), which
previously enrolled only the Party elite, have recently been eyed
by private businessmen as excellent training centers.
</P>
<P>
Created by the Party's committees at different levels, Party
schools are characterized by a special educational system designed
to spread Marxism among cadres. Doctoral programs are available
for the most distinguished students.
</P>
<P>
Now, courses targeting private businessmen have been launched
in Party schools at both central and local levels. Sources say
that the enthusiasm for applying a seat in a Party school is
soaring, particularly in the coastal regions where the market
economy is on a fast track.
</P>
<P>
-- The death toll from an explosion at a fireworks factory
Friday morning in Jiangmen, south China's Guangdong Province, has
risen to 36, and 160 others have been reported injured.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 people are still missing following the blast,
which investigators believe may have occurred when sparks produced
by employees pounding iron nails ignited inside the warehouse
building.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin has expressed deep concern over
the recent fireworks explosion in south China's Guangdong Province,
and the State Council has ordered local governments and
departments concerned to take immediate measures to ensure
industrial safety.
</P>
<P>
-- China has renewed administrative measures governing Sino-
overseas joint-venture hospitals and clinics, hoping the sector's
sound development can provide people a wide range of health care
services.
</P>
<P>
According to a rule published by ministries of Health and
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, which went into effect on
July 1, overseas hospitals and firms can launch joint ventures in
China after they get permission from the two ministries.
</P>
</TEXT>
