<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai B-share Market Weekly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai B-share market was
mixed with a strong negative bias this week (July 3rd--7th),
reflecting the overall uncertain sentiment set in the broader
market.
</P>
<P>
The B-share index fell 1.16 points, or 2.07 percent, to 54.86
this week, according to Homeway, China's leading on-line financial
and securities advisory company.
</P>
<P>
The turnover was 66.83 million U.S. dollars (554.69 million
yuan), little changed from last week's total at 65.78 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The earnings warning from over 30 stocks so far kept the
broader market on edge for most of the time amid speculation that
more companies will soon be issuing warnings of their own.
Negative announcements have been running a little high.
</P>
<P>
The market failed to hold on to a positive bias and any advance
continued to be restricted. But generally speaking, the downside
pressure proved modest and short lived as the cyclical issues came
to life now and then.
</P>
<P>
The market did stabilize before the weekend as thoughts of the
accelerating reforms in China's stock market paced the way on the
upside during the recovery off the sessions low.
</P>
<P>
China will encourage foreign-invested companies to seek listing
either on the yuan-denominated A-share market or the foreign
currency B-share market, the first official confirmation since
British consumer goods market Unilever Plc filed its application
for a listing on China's A-share market last Friday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it is said China's securities regulator is
considering a proposal to let companies that already trade their
stocks as H shares on the Hong Kong market sell yuan-denominated A
shares in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the market seemed to have rather muted reactions,
insisting that earnings profile is still the most important factor
in determining the near-term direction. That was the key factor
why the index had not been pulled out of the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
Gains will not be overtly aggressive next week, given the
numerous earning warnings and negative comments. The market
performance is not likely to be very impressive for a period of
time, Home analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
