<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Urges Allies to Rally Public Support for Peace Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
is urging his left-wing allies to get mobilized to rally public
support for his peace efforts as he prepares to leave for a pivotal
three-way summit the United States.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with One Israel ministers on Thursday, Barak said
he regrets that the left is not organizing demonstrations or
raising posters to show support publicly for the peace process and
he is worried that right-wing activists will be the only presence
on the streets to make themselves seen and heard.
</P>
<P>
Barak will meet again Friday with senior figures of his leftist
Labor Party, the backbone of One Israel bloc, to try to ignite
grassroots support for the government.
</P>
<P>
Barak has instructed his ministers and Labor Party Secretary-
General Ra'anan Cohen to get their own activists onto the streets.
He also asked Minister of Immigrant Absorption Yuli Tamir and
coalition chairman Ophir Pines-Paz to coordinate activity with
peace movements outside the Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin was entrusted with coordination in
the Knesset to ensure parliamentary majority for the law
establishing a referendum if an agreement is reached with the
Palestinians at the upcoming summit at Camp David, a presidential
resort in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the council of settlements and the joint
operations staff of the right-wing movements are preparing
extensive protest activities before and during next week's summit
called by U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Their plans include a hunger strike opposite Barak's residence
in Jerusalem and a huge rally in Rabin Square in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The council declared on Thursday a "state of emergency" and
ordered the heads of all the settlements to cease their activities
and fight against the evacuation of settlements and territories.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which will begin next Tuesday with the participation
of Clinton, Barak, and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, will try
to resolve the key issues in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks
such as Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees, borders, Jewish
settlements and water.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will try to reach a framework agreement before the
September target date for a final peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Preparations are underway for the summit and Israeli Public
Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami and Palestinian Council Speaker
Ahmed Qurei will travel to Washington over the weekend and meet
with U.S. officials to get things ready.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, shortly after Clinton announced to host the
summit, Ysrael Ba'aliya, a right-wing partner in Barak's coalition
government, announced resignation from the government. Another
right-wing partner, the National Religious Party (NRP), decided
Thursday to resign.
</P>
<P>
Facing the fresh threats to the coalition, Barak has appealed
for national unity and urged the two ruling partners to recede
their resignation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
