<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs from
the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The Black Sea Economic Cooperation Organization
(BSECO) and the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization
(FAO) held a conference in Istanbul Thursday to discuss food
security and agriculture strategy.
</P>
<P>
Head of FAO's Ankara Office Maharaj Muthoo said that many of the
BSECO countries had slipped into greater poverty with more people
living below poverty line.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, which has been self-sufficient in food production,
pledged to do its best to establish cooperation with Black Sea
countries to fight against aggravating hunger and malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
BSECO has 11 member countries: Albania, Armenia, Azerbaijan,
Bulgaria, Georgia, Greece, Moldova, Romania, Russia, Turkey and
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- A Siemens AG-led consortium has won an order worth 1.
44 billion dollars to build a power station in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The twin-unit hard-coal-fired power station will have a capacity
of 2 x 650 megawatts and be located close to the southern Turkish
city of Iskenderun, Siemens said in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Siemens Power Generation Group (KWU), the
consortium comprises Germany's Babock Borsig power and Turkey's
Gama-Tekfen.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A draft proposal aimed at speeding up the
privatization of Bezeq, a state-owned communications firm, was
issued early in the week by Yaron Jacobs, director general of the
Government Companies Authority.
</P>
<P>
Communications Minister Binyamin Ben-Eliezer has ordered that
Bezeq be privatized within 15 months.
</P>
<P>
The principles of the proposed privatization were presented to
the Bezeq board of directors last week. Under the proposal, at
least 50 percent of the company's shares would be offered to a
private investor, who could purchase a portion of the shares
immediately and retain an option for acquiring an additional stake
at a later date.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli Finance Ministry will submit a proposal
to the Knesset (parliament) within a month on easing the tax
burdens on high-tech industries. The proposal was approved earlier
this week by the ministerial committee on legislation.
</P>
<P>
Tax commission said it was impossible to estimate what impact
the changes would have on tax revenues in the short term, since no
one knows how many high-tech companies will be set up or their
scale.
</P>
<P>
However, they added, most of the proposed changes will merely
defer tax collection rather than reduce it.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Moody's, an authoritative international credit
rating company, Thursday announced it was raising Israel's credit
rating from A minus to A (A3 to A2) and raised Israel's short-term
credit rating from P2 to P1, their highest rating available for
short-term credit. The rating enables Israel to raise funds
internationally at lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The decision, taken unanimously by Moody's credit committee, was
explained as a result of Israel's modern broad-based economy, with
a strong high-tech sector, which leads in exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
