<HEADLINE> Ties Between Indonesia, Australia Back to Normal Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The relations between Indonesia and
Australia which has been deteriorated over the last year is
expected to go back to normal within next one to two years, a
senior official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"That is not a big deal. And I think our relations with
Australia will back to normal within next one to two years. And I
don't see any obstacles," Indonesian Minister of Defense Juwono
Sudarsono told Xinhua in an exclusive interview.
</P>
<P>
"Our relations with Australia just have been influenced by East
Timor's issue. Don't be exaggerated. And now, East Timor is no
longer part of Indonesia's territory," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that, "there is no problem in connection with our
military ties with Australia," adding that some Australian
military officers are still continuing their studies in Indonesia
and the same thing with Indonesian military officers in Australia.
</P>
<P>
"And we don't see Australia as a threat," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about East Timor issue, Sudarsono said it all depends on
the United Nations (U.N.).
</P>
<P>
"East Timor (destiny) depends on the implementation of the U.N.
's promises. So far, East Timorese were only given promises by the
U.N., but nothing (of its promises) has been met by the U.N.," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the U.N. only questioned cases of human right
abuse which were allegedly committed by personnel of the
Indonesian Military (TNI). " Whereas, it is more important to
think about the future of East Timorese, (think about) their
education and their social welfare. East Timorese have been bored
to be regulated and dictated by the U.N., the United States,
Australia and Indonesia," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
