<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's White Farmers Offer 400 More Farms for Resettlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Commercial Farmers' Union of
Zimbabwe has offered a further 400 farms for the government's
resettlement program, bringing its total offer to 600, the weekly
Business reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
If the land reform is done properly, the union can easily give
the additional 400 farms, Deputy Director of the Union Jerry Grant
said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Grant said out of the gazetted list of 804 farms, more than 270
were possessed by the sole owners and so they should not be on the
list for compulsory acquisition.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the government will abandon the
compulsory acquisition and only target multiple owners and
derelict land.
</P>
<P>
Grant said it did not intend to frustrate the government's
efforts to implement its land reform and resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
"We must get the politics out of the land issue and deal with
it as an economic issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to obstruct the government's resettlement
program, but productive farms should be left to those fully
utilizing them," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Grant said farmers had contested the acquisition of more than
500 farms.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Lands and Agriculture is going through
submissions made by white farmers objecting to the compulsory
acquisition of their farms.
</P>
<P>
However, the government can still go ahead issuing acquisition
orders for the farms despite white farmers' objections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
