<HEADLINE> Kenya to Import More Power From Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Uganda will increase its power
export to Kenya from the current 10 megawatts to 80 megawatts,
Kenyan Energy Minister Francis Lotodo has said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's leading newspapers Friday quoted the minister as saying
the supply is expected in mid-July and will ease the ongoing power
crisis.
</P>
<P>
From late May, the Kenyan government introduced an intensifying
power rationing due to a long dry spell which has led to the low
levels of reservoirs, seriously affecting the country's power
generation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a crowd outside the parliament buildings here
Thursday, Lotodo said his government will import two "massive"
generators, each with 55 megawatts, to alleviate the power
shortage.
</P>
<P>
The two generating units will be located in Nakuru and Eldoret
cities in Rift Valley Province, central Kenya, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Kenya now faces a shortage of 100 megawatts. 
</P>
