<HEADLINE> Zambian Government Urged to Pay Debt Owed to Suppliers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has been
urged to raise money to pay debt owed to the companies which
supplied goods to the former state-run Zambia Consolidated Copper
Mines, currently a private company.
</P>
<P>
The mining corporation owes the suppliers about 400 billion
Kwacha (about 133 million U.S. dollars), which the government has
promised to liquidate through monthly budgetary allocations,
according to Zambia Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper Friday quoted President of the Zambia Federation
of Employers Samuel Musonda as saying here Thursday that the
monthly liquidation of debt is not enough to make them viable.
</P>
<P>
He said that foreign companies are being awarded supplying
tenders by new mine owners because the Zambian companies are
facing serious financial difficulties due to the delay by the
government in paying the debt.
</P>
<P>
The failure by the former state-owned mining corporation to pay
the debt has caused the suppliers to fail to execute the contracts
awarded by new owners of the mines, said Musonda.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, the new mine owners are being forced to look to
foreign suppliers," Musonda said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the government would quickly attend to the issue
of liquidating the debt.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March this year, privatization of the former
mining corporation had been completed in a bid to attract foreign
investment and advanced technology and management to revive the
ailing mining industry in the copper-producing country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
