<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Earns Over $80M Through Mineral Exports Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania earned a total of
80.4 million U.S. dollars through mineral exports last year,
almost a four-fold increase from 22.6 million dollars in 1998, the
official Daily News reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Minister for Energy and Minerals Abdallah
Kigoda as saying that the achievement was due to the production of
gold in the western Tabora Region and the increased output of
diamonds in the northern Shinyanga Region.
</P>
<P>
Export of precious stones also increased from 8.1 million
dollars in 1998 to 14 million dollars last year, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, many local exporters of raw precious stones
failed to fetch good prices for their products in the world market
despite enjoying royalty exemption.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister also admitted that many international
investors in the mining sector were scared away by numerous taxes
and red-tape in some public institutions in Tanzania, adding that
taxes had greatly contributed to smuggling of minerals abroad.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 10 years Tanzania has experienced the expansion
of the mining sector which in turn has resulted in the increase of
export earnings.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of the sector is a relief to the eastern African
country, whose major source of foreign exchange has been
traditional cash crops, which are bringing in less foreign income
as their volumes and prices fall.
</P>
<P>
According to industry officials, Tanzania is expected to emerge
among Africa's top mineral producers after South Africa and Ghana.
The sector will soon be contributing 40 percent of the country's
GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
