<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher in Tokyo
Friday, led mainly by high-priced information and technology (IT)
issues which were boosted by Thursday's rebound in New York's
Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 115.87 points, or 0.67
percent, from Thursday's close to end at 17,398.24.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 6.73 points, or 0.42 percent, to 1,597.
36.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 735.03 million
shares from Thursday's 689.37 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Friday's launch of new investment trusts also helped share
prices move higher, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Electric wire and cable makers drew buying on expectations for
further development in IT-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
Gainers included nonferrous metal makers, wholesalers and
nonbank moneylenders, while the rubber, air transportation and
insurance sectors faced selling.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers narrowly
exceeded gainers 636 to 609 despite the rises in the Nikkei and
TOPIX, with 150 issues closing unchanged. 
