<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4,000-year-old Percussion Instrument Unearthed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- A rectangular stone musical
instrument, confirmed to be a type of percussion instrument used
in ancient China, was recently unearthed at the site of Qijia
Culture in Qinghai Province, northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists from the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (
CASS) and the Qinghai Provincial Archaeological Research Institute
said that this is the first such instrument ever found in the
history of Chinese archaeology.
</P>
<P>
They said that the discovery may reverse the traditional theory
that ancient percussion instruments were triangular-shaped or
square.
</P>
<P>
The Qijia Culture flourished in the transitional period from
the Neolithic Age to the Bronze Age, some 3,500 to 4,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Wang Renxiang, a researcher from the CASS, discovered the relic
at the home of a farmer who lives in the Lajia village, where the
ruins of the Qijia Culture are located.
</P>
<P>
The finely-cut and well-polished instrument, 96 cm long and 66
cm wide, is dark blue and still produces a loud, clear sound.
</P>
<P>
A number of jade articles used in primitive religious rituals
were found at the site, as well as a city moat which is dozens
meters wide and five meters deep, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Based on the discovery, experts from the CASS and Qinghai
Provincial Archaeological Research Institute concluded that the
site may have been the center of an administrative region.
</P>
<P>
They also estimated that the ruins cover an area of 200,000 to
300,000 sq m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Prepares for Yellow River Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 7 (Xinhua) -- China has mobilized 3.05 million
people along the Yellow River to make preparations for a possible
flood.
</P>
<P>
Sources with the Yellow River Flood Prevention Headquarters
said that the country is transporting mountains of sand bags,
fortification materials and rafts to the river valley, while
reinforcing the dykes.
</P>
<P>
Although north China is being affected by severe drought,
officials say that flooding could still be the biggest danger on
the Yellow River, the country's second longest river, which is
noted for disastrous floods in history.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 bank bursts have been reported on the river
over the past 3,000 years, some leaving millions of people
homeless and big cities destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the riverbed has been continuing to rise these
years because of an accumulation of silt, and future floods will
be even more devastating.
</P>
<P>
Although the country has built dozens of reservoirs on the
river, some of them are in disrepair and cannot prevent big floods.
</P>
<P>
Officials warned that as the Yellow River region has
experienced ten straight years of drought, many people have become
complacent about the possibility of flooding.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
