<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- An exposition showing more than 3,000 unique and valuable
costumes worn by various ethnic minority groups in China opened in
Kunming, capital of southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
Among the items on display, there is a patched coat of fish
skins, which is typical of the traditional costume of the Hezhe
people, who live in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, and a
Tibetan costume worth more than 800,000 yuan (about 97,000 U.S.
dollars), which is some 300 or 400 years old.
</P>
<P>
The Exposition of Ethnic Clothing and Decorations, co-hosted by
the State Ethnic Affairs Commission and the Yunnan provincial
government, is the first of its kind ever held in China, which is
home to 56 nationalities.
</P>
<P>
-- In the wake of a string of boating accidents, China's
Ministry of Communications has started conducting a month-long
safety check on the rural township passenger and ferry boats.
</P>
<P>
The check will consist of supervising the implementation of a
boat safety management responsibility system at the county and
rural township government levels, and standardize the granting of
business licenses for rural township passenger and ferry boats.
</P>
<P>
-- China is going all out to fight against a devastating
drought that has ravaged northern China. More than 40 million
people are battling the severe drought every day, said officials
from the State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
-- Sinopec International turned out to be China's largest
foreign trade company among the country's top 500, and the
Shanghai-based Orient International (Holdings) Co. Ltd., the
largest exporter among the country's top 200, according to an
official chart made public by the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
-- China's top legislature, the Standing Committee of the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC), started its 16th session to
deliberate nine draft laws on product quality, customs, and patent
rights, farm seeds and the trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Professor Yang Huanming, chief scientist of the human genome
project in China, Zhang Meng, a researcher with the Beijing
Genomics Institute and other scientists and research groups were
awarded by the Genetics Institute of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Science and Technology will provide three
million yuan (about 360,000 US dollars) more to support the genome
research center.
</P>
<P>
-- State Drug Administration of China has approved the
production and sale of Viagra, the best-selling impotence drug, in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Viagra will be available at general hospitals at county level
or above, but only with a doctor's prescription.
</P>
<P>
-- China's Xinhua News Agency released a commentary on July 3
urging local governments to give priority to the safety of people'
s lives and property.
</P>
<P>
The commentary notes that the blind pursuit of profits by some
departments caused them to dare to ignore the central government's
regulations on industrial safety.
</P>
<P>
The article demands that severe punishment be given to the
people responsible for accidents that result in the loss of people
's lives and property according to law.
</P>
<P>
-- The Fengyun 2 meteorological satellite, launched June 25 by
means of a Long March 3 carrier rocket from the Xichang Satellite
Launch Center in southwest China's Sichuan Province, was
successfully positioned in a geostationary orbit on schedule.
</P>
<P>
-- Two giant panda cubs from southwest China's Sichuan Province
-- Mei Xiang and Tian Tian -- have been selected as gifts to the
United States soon.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Wolong Nature Reserve disclosed that the
female Mei Xiang is two years old and weighs 60 kilograms, while
her future husband Tian Tian is one year older and weighs 95
kilograms.
</P>
<P>
-- China started a three-month campaign to combat illegal drug
and food advertisements with a notice issued by the State
Administration for Industry and Commerce (SAIT).
</P>
<P>
The notice came amidst surging complaints from consumers about
fake and exaggerated drug and food advertisements in recent months.
</P>
<P>
The offenses of such advertisements include exaggeration of
contents, coverage by the media in the form of scientific or
special reports, citing names of doctors, experts and patients
without approval, and so on, the notice pointed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
