<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daily Air Quality Report for Chinese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The air quality of the 42 cities in
China declined during the past 24 hours (from 12:00 yesterday to
12:00 today) with Beijing, Changsha, Lanzhou, Xining and Urumqi
reporting slight air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Six cities, namely, Fuzhou, Xiamen, Zhengzhou, Zhanjiang,
Haikou and Lhasa reported excellent air, according to the daily
air quality report issued by the China Environmental Monitoring
Center today.
</P>
<P>
level-two or fairly good air quality was reported in 31 cities:
Tianjin, Shijiazhuang, Taiyuan, Hohhot, Shenyang, Dalian,
Changchun, Harbin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Nantong, Hangzhou,
Wenzhou, Hefei, Nanchang, Jinan, Qingdao, Yantai, Wuhan, Guangzhou,
Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Shantou, Nanning, Chongqing, Chengdu, Guiyang,
Kunming, Xi'an and Yinchuan.
</P>
<P>
Particulate matter less than 10 microns in size was the major
pollutant in most of these cities, except Shijiazhuang, Changsha,
Shenzhen, Nanjing, Chongqing, Guiyang, and Kunming, where sulfur
dioxide was the major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into
five levels: level-one or excellent (pollution indexes below 50),
level-two or fairly good (pollution indexes ranging from 50 to 100)
, level-three or slightly polluted (pollution indexes ranging from
101-200), level-four or poor (pollution indexes ranging from 201
to 300) and level-five or hazardous (pollution indexes over 301).
</P>
<P>
The 42 cities monitored include the four municipalities of
Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing, provincial capitals, and
major cities in economically developed coastal areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
