<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Israeli newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak Thursday appealed for
national unity in advance of next week's Camp David summit, saying
the country is at an "historic crossroads" that could change its
future.
</P>
<P>
He also cautioned against exaggerated expectations of the
meetings and said the chances of success are 50-50.
</P>
<P>
Fresh threats to the unity of Barak's coalition also emerged as
regards the upcoming summit. Eli Yishai, leader of the ultra-
Orthodox Shas party has already turned down an offer to accompany
Barak to Camp David.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Supreme Court justices Thursday harshly criticized,
and expressed their amazement over, the cabinet's appointment of
Knesset (Parliament) Member Yossi Katz from the ruling One Israel
bloc as ambassador to Germany.
</P>
<P>
The Movement for Quality Government in Israel appealed against
the nomination and the court suggested domestic politics had played
a key role in the appointment, saying that it frees up a Knesset
seat for Foreign Minister David Levy's close associate Moti
Mishani.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- The current heatwave in Israel caused a tragedy on Thursday
when an 18-year-old American girl died from dehydration on a hiking
trip in a cave in the desert area in the southeast part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The girl was with a group of 12 American and English tourists
who traveled to the cave by mini-bus from Jerusalem Thursday
morning and apparently did not bring enough water with them to the
desert, where temperature neared 40 degrees.
</P>
<P>
A police helicopter and rescue team located the victim's body
near the cave at about 2 p.m..
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The case against Israeli former Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and his wife is likely to be closed by Attorney General
Elyakim Rubinstein following a recommendation to that effect by
Jerusalem District Attorney Moshe Lador.
</P>
<P>
Lador submitted what officials described as a well-grounded
brief of about 200 pages explaining why he thinks the state would
find it difficult to get a conviction in court against the former
prime minister and his wife on the basis of the available evidence.
</P>
<P>
The police recommended last March that Netanyahu be indicted on
charges of bribe taking, fraud, breach of trust and obstructing
justice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
