<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Support Kenya's Poverty Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The British government plans to
provide 30 million pounds (about 58.6 million U.S. dollars) to
Kenya to help implement its poverty reduction strategy, media here
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the British High Commission in Nairobi, the
support which will be made available during the current calendar
year will go a long way in helping Kenya implement its poverty
reduction strategy.
</P>
<P>
The money will assist in the civil service reform which is aimed
at improving the performance of the public sector in delivering
key services to the people, particularly the poor, the media said.
</P>
<P>
However, the British High Commission said here Thursday that
the availability of the funds depended on whether International
Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank boards approve new assistance
to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The IMF board will meet on July 26 to discuss its planned new
assistance to Kenya, and the World Bank is expected to hold a
similar meeting.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the British High Commission disclosed that
Britain may make further support available later in the 2000/2001
Kenyan financial year depending on the progress in the
implementation of its economic reform and poverty reduction
program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
