<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Asks for Effective Peacekeeping Mission at Border With Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has demanded that the
United Nations peacekeeping mission to be deployed in the buffer
zone between Ethiopia and Eritrea be efficient and effective.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Herald newspaper Friday quoted Foreign Minister
Seyoum Mesfin as saying that the U.N. peacekeeping mission should
be able to fully cover the security zone and monitor military
activities in both countries.
</P>
<P>
The mission should also strengthen its humanitarian affairs
section to deal effectively with the suffering of innocent
Ethiopians in Eritrea, he said, adding that a lasting solution to
Ethio-Eritrean conflict could be reached only if the suffering of
up to 25,000 Ethiopians in Eritrea is given a definitive end.
</P>
<P>
Seyoum made the remarks Thursday while conferring with the U.N.
 reconnaissance mission led by Major General Timothy Ford.
</P>
<P>
In response, Ford said that his team would report Ethiopia's
demands to the U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peacekeeping mission will open a liaison office in
Addis Ababa, capital of Ethiopia, to undertake its mission
smoothly, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
Since its arrival here Tuesday night, the five-member mission
has held talks with the Ethiopian government and military
officials. They are due to leave for Asmara, Eritrea on similar
mission this weekend. 
</P>
</TEXT>
