<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Private Sector Loses 50,000 Jobs This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's private sector has lost
at least 50,000 jobs since the beginning of this year owing to a
deepening economic crisis, the weekly Business reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The situation will worsen if the pressing problems persist,
like fuel shortages, a staggering domestic and foreign debt, a
ballooning deficit, high inflation and interest rates, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
President of the Employers Confederation of Zimbabwe Joshua
Nyoka told the weekly that the number of retrenchment was likely
to swell to 100,000 by the end of the year if the problems were
not resolved as a matter of urgency.
</P>
<P>
"Companies in the agriculture, shipping, fertilizer and other
sectors have been hit hard because of the managed exchange rate.
As a result, about 54,000 people who had been fully employed have
lost their jobs in the last six months," Nyoka said.
</P>
<P>
"We are also aware of companies that are now operating on a
three-day working week," he said.
</P>
<P>
General business optimism has plunged to an all time low in
eight years with the manufacturing sector being affected worst, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
