<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Childhood Immunizations Reaches Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A record percentage of U.S.
preschool children have received recommended immunizations to
protect them from childhood diseases, but more needs to be done,
federal health officials said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Immunization coverage has been rising steadily since 1993, but
about 20 percent of American toddlers remain vulnerable to
diseases because they are not fully immunized, the Atlanta-based
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDCP) said.
</P>
<P>
Among children aged 19 months to 35 months, 95.9 percent had
received the recommended three doses of the diphtheria, tetanus
and pertussis vaccine in 1999, and 93.5 percent had been
vaccinated for Haemophilus influenza type b (Hib).
</P>
<P>
The CDCP, basing its figures on a telephone survey of 33,548
households, estimated that 91.5 percent had received the vaccine
covering measles, mumps and rubella and 88.1 percent had received
the recommended three doses of hepatitis B vaccine.
</P>
<P>
Coverage levels for several vaccines increased from 1998 to
1999, the CDCP said, while coverage for poliovirus vaccine
remained relatively unchanged at 89.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
An increasing percentage of children have received the
chickenpox vaccine introduced in the mid-1990s. The chickenpox
vaccination rate rose to 59.4 percent in 1999, the CDCP said.
</P>
<P>
Deaths and illnesses from diphtheria, pertussis, tetanus,
measles, mumps, rubella and Hib are at or near record lows because
of the high vaccination levels, the CDCP said.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks in large part to these high immunization rates, we have
seen a breathtaking decline in suffering and death from most
vaccine-preventable diseases," Health and Human Services Secretary
Donna Shalala said in a statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
