Shanghai Five" summit. (Turkmenistan-Jiang-Departure)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton was Thursday warned
by 50 Nobel laureates on the proposed National Missile Defense (
NMD) shield.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Clinton, the U.S. scientists warned that the
deployment of such a system would be "premature, wasteful, and
dangerous." They believed that the 60-billion-dollar system "would
offer little protection and would do grave harm to this nation's
core security interests. "They expressed concern that the U.S.
decision would spark arms race across the world. (US-NMD-Warning)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Describing Kashmir as a "nuclear flash point",
Pakistani President Rafiq Tarar Thursday called on the
international community to persuade India to enter into meaningful
dialogue with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"The world has now come to realize that durable peace between
Pakistan and India cannot be achieved without addressing the core
issue of Kashmir on priority basis," he stated while addressing a
function at the National Defense College of Pakistan. "Kashmir is
a test case of the viability and credibility of the present
international order," he added. The president regretted that the
attitude of the Indian government has not been conducive to peace.
"Their leaders continue to make bellicose and provocative
statements to build up war hysteria," he said. (Pakistan-India-
Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Yugoslav Federal Assembly on Thursday approved
major constitutional amendments concerning the election and re-
election of the president.
</P>
<P>
Under the amendments, the Yugoslav president will be directly
elected by the public, instead of by the Federal Assembly, and can
hold two terms of office. Under the current constitution, the
president's tenure is an unrenewable four-year term. Observers
believe that the amendments have paved the way for President
Slobodan Milosevic's re-election after his current term of office
expires in 2001. (Yugoslavia-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian Defense Minister Juwono Sudarsono said
that supporters of former president Soeharto are fomenting unrest
to escape justice and destabilize the government.
</P>
<P>
"Based on our intelligence reports there are strong indications
that former cronies of Soeharto are supplying arms and personnel
to areas afflicted with conflicts, particularly in the Malukus,
East Timor, West Irian and certainly in Aceh," Sudarsono was
quoted by the Jakarta Post Friday as saying. He said that the
trouble makers were "a group of cronies who have managed to
abandon ship at the last minute. There are strong indications that
the cronies, not necessarily from the Cendana (the street where
Soeharto and his family live) family, are certainly involved in
some of the unrest and bombings in North Sumatra, part of East
Java and the Malukus," he said. But Sudarsono said it was "quite
difficult" to find the evidence as these people have been working
under the so-called "cell system." (Indonesia-Soeharto) 
</P>
