<HEADLINE> New Zealand Unhappy With Soccer Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Sport, Fitness and
Leisure Minister Trevor Mallard said here Friday that the New
Zealand government is "extremely unhappy and disappointed with
Charlie Dempsey's role in the demise of South Africa's World Cup
Soccer bid."
</P>
<P>
Germany and South Africa had been neck and neck with 11 votes
each and in the final and decisive third round at FIFA House in
Zurich, Switzerland Germany snatched a last-minute winner 12-11
because New Zealand's Dempsey, who was the Oceania member,
abstained from voting.
</P>
<P>
"I'm shocked that one individual seems to have abused his
voting right by disregarding instructions on voting requirements,"
Minister Mallard said in a government press release.
</P>
<P>
"As Oceania's representative, Mr. Dempsey was under instruction
to support the South African bid, once England had dropped out of
the ballot. The government was aware of those instructions and
fully supported them.
</P>
<P>
"Though his abandonment of his delegation, Mr. Dempsey has
damaged the international reputation of the entire country as well
as the sport of soccer in New Zealand. His actions could cast
doubt on New Zealand's reliability on the international stage,"
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He added the World Cup finals have never been held in Africa
and he is distressed that New Zealand is associated with that
chance being blown. 
</P>
</TEXT>
