<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand to Open Diplomatic Post in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand has promised that it
will open a diplomatic post in East Timor, which will announce its
independence next year.
</P>
<P>
The promise was given by New Zealand Foreign Minister Phil Goff,
when he was meeting here Friday with visiting President of the
National Council of Timorese Resistance (CNRT) Xanana Gusmao, who
is expected to be East Timor's first president after general
elections late next year.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat, yet to be named, will be New Zealand's liaison
officer to the United Nations Transitional Administration in East
Timor (UNTAET) and he would liaise with both UNTAET and CNRT and
monitor New Zealand's assistance, including recruiting East
Timorese to come to New Zealand to study and train, Goff told
Gusmao.
</P>
<P>
But no decision has been made whether an embassy will be opened
once the territory becomes independent.
</P>
<P>
Goff said the New Zealand government seeks to strengthen its
relationship with the fledgling nation.
</P>
<P>
He said he expects to start scaling down the deployment of New
Zealand troops in East Timor later this year.
</P>
<P>
There are 660 New Zealand troops there at present.
</P>
<P>
Gusmao said East Timor is keen to have a close relationship
with New Zealand and he realizes the deployment of troops in East
Timor is a heavy burden for New Zealand, but they are essential to
maintaining security and stability.
</P>
<P>
He said East Timor is developing its own armed forces but he
hopes peacekeepers will remain in the country until "we have a
guarantee that nothing can happen."
</P>
<P>
One of the reasons for promoting reconciliation within East
Timor and with its neighbor Indonesia, despite its 25-year
occupation, is to ensure stability of the territory, Gusmao said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
