<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Crews Still Battle Wildfires in Colorado, Wyoming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Frustrated by strong wind gusts,
high temperatures and bone-dry land, firefighters have made little
headway in containing three wildfires burning in remote areas of
western Colorado, and two more in Wyoming, local officials
reported late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
No injuries have been reported and no structures have been
damaged by the Colorado blazes, which are confined primarily to
public lands, according to federal fire officials in Grand
Junction.
</P>
<P>
The Buster Flats fire, the largest of the Colorado wildfires,
has burned at least 9,500 acres of land in the northwest corner of
the state, 30 kilometers from the border with Wyoming. No
structures have been directly threatened, but authorities
evacuated the nearby Gates of Ladore and Brown's National Wildlife
Refuge campgrounds as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
"There was a period in the afternoon where we had to pull the
crews off because of the wind, and the fire made some strong runs
downhill," according to fire information officer Dennis Saville.
</P>
<P>
The fire is naturally contained by the Green River on the north
and east, and firefighters have contained another 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Another 800 acres have been consumed by a second fire in
northwest Colorado, while the third fire is burning to the south,
near the town of Gateway. Approximately 3,000 acres have burned
since Monday. The fire has quadrupled in size since it was first
detected.
</P>
<P>
"We were real dry and it's not good to have wind behind the
fire," said Bill Kight, a spokesman for the fire center. He said
that winds gusts have reached 50 kph. Officials are using air
tankers, helicopters and land crews to battle the blazes, which
threaten three homes and several historical mining-camp structures.
</P>
<P>
"We're praying for rain," he said. No rain, however, is
forecast for the area for the next few days.
</P>
<P>
In Wyoming, two wildfires had scorched about 22,500 acres of
juniper and sagebrush. No structures were threatened but one
firefighter was treated for heat stroke, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The fire season is shaping up as the worst since 1996,
according to the National Interagency Fire Center in Idaho. It
began more than a month ago with blazes engulfing areas of Florida
and the Southwest, most notably in Los Alamos, New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
About 44,300 fires covering more than 1.2 million acres have
been recorded nationwide so far, with drought getting worse in the
West. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
