<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: U.S. Men Have Worse Health Habits Than Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A new study released Thursday
shows that U.S. men are more likely to be smokers, drinkers or
overweight than women, and less likely to have health insurance or
wear seat belts.
</P>
<P>
The differences between men and women were detailed by the
Atlanta-based Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDCP),
using statistics from telephone surveys of tens of thousands of
adults in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
The CDCP said that 62.2 percent of men and 44.5 percent of
women said they were overweight in 1997. Experts said being
overweight increased the risk of chronic health problems such as
high blood pressure, diabetes, heart disease and some cancers.
</P>
<P>
Researchers said 25.3 percent of men were smokers, compared
with 21.1 percent of women. The CDCP noted that cigarette smoking
was a major cause of illness and death in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Men were more than three times as likely as women to have
engaged in binge drinking during the past month, defined by the
government as having at least five drinks on one occasion. More
than 22 percent of men were binge drinkers, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
Men were almost seven times as likely as women to report
chronic drinking, or having 60 or more alcoholic beverages during
the previous month, the CDCP said. More than five percent of men
were chronic drinkers, the study found.
</P>
<P>
Alcohol abuse is the leading cause of liver-related mortality
in the United States and is associated with hypertension, heart
disease, and stroke, the CDCP said.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that men were more than three times as
likely as women to report drinking and driving. The CDCP said 74.8
percent of women and 61.9 percent of men said they always wore a
seat belt.
</P>
<P>
About 15.2 percent of men said they had no health insurance,
compared with 13.5 percent of women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
