<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Modernize its Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Defense Minister Juwono
Sudarsono said here Friday that Indonesia will modernize its
military equipment to adjust to new developments in the region and
deal with any possible threats from outside.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua at his office, the
minister said that Indonesia plans to purchase weapons, ammunition
and other military equipment including warships and submarines
from foreign countries to meet the need of its military equipment.
Indonesia also wanted to purchase weapon from China, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Now, we have been calculating accurately, what we need. What
kind of weapons may we need now and in the future," the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
The modernization of the Indonesian Military's (TNI) weaponry
system is in line with our policy in reforming our national
defense system, he said.
</P>
<P>
"But, now we are still facing obstacles due to economic crisis
and lack of fund. So if you ask me how long the modernization
process (in our military) will be, I would say it takes around 5-
10 years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sudarsono also disclosed that the number of TNI is currently
very limited compared to the number of the country's inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
"Now, the number of the Indonesian Army is just around 230,000,
The Navy 40,000 and the Air Force is between 20,000 and 25,000,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Ideally, the number of our military personnel should be two
and a half fold of the current figure. But may be it will take 5
to 7 years to reach such an ideal figure," he said.
</P>
<P>
"And the success of our program will depend on the country's
economic condition. If our economic could recover soon, our
program will be fast or could be accelerated," the minister
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Sudarsono also said that the TNI now has been launching an
internal reforms and," in connection with such an internal reforms
we will change our doctrines and defense concepts in line with our
constitution. We hope that sometime, in due course, the TNI will
become a professional and respected institution." 
</P>
</TEXT>
