<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Healthy Lifestyle Cuts Heart Risk by 80 Percent for Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A study released Thursday shows
that eating right, exercising and not smoking can reduce the risk
of heart disease by 80 percent for women.
</P>
<P>
"I was surprised the magnitude was so large -- over 80 percent
reduction in risk," said study leader Dr. Meir Stampfer of Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
The results are published in this week's New England Journal of
Medicine.
</P>
<P>
Stampfer and other researchers at Harvard tracked the
lifestyles of 84,129 women nurses during 14 years and measured
their susceptibility to heart disease -- the number-one killer of
adult Americans.
</P>
<P>
The women with the lowest risk for heart disease didn't smoke,
ate a healthy diet, exercised at least 30 minutes a day,
maintained a good weight and consumed no alcohol or drank in
moderation (two glasses of wine per day, for example), reported
the researchers.
</P>
<P>
Those results reaffirm what doctors have long believed. "The
vast majority of heart disease could be eliminated if everyone
adopted a healthy lifestyle," Dr. Stampfer said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Nanette Wenger, Emory University School of Medicine,
Atlanta, said the study's results are what "most of us who believe
so strongly in prevention would want to see -- the fact that women
who do very simple lifestyle interventions get benefits."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Warned on Missile Defense Plan by Nobel Laureates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton was
Thursday warned by 50 Nobel laureates on the proposed National
Missile Defense (NMD) shield.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Clinton, the U.S. scientists warned that the
deployment of such a system would be "premature, wasteful, and
dangerous."
</P>
<P>
They believed that the 60-billion-dollar system "would offer
little protection and would do grave harm to this nation's core
security interests."
</P>
<P>
They expressed concern that the U.S. decision would spark arms
race across the world.
</P>
<P>
France on Thursday also warned Washington of the dangerous
consequences from the deployment of the NMD.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the United States does not make the decision
without measuring the consequences for their European allies and
the reactions of China and Russia," said French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
He said that the NMD risks provoking negative and dangerous
reactions from certain countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
"The reaction of France and other member countries of the
European Union (EU) will depend on that of Russia," he told
representatives of parliament members of the EU countries and
those of 12 candidates for EU membership who met in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said that France and other EU members will give a
strong response if the U.S. unilaterally launches the NMD without
obtaining the agreement of Russia.
</P>
<P>
The new warnings came as the Pentagon plans to launch a third
test for the NMD on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has received many similar warnings before.
</P>
<P>
On June 29, a group of 45 U.S. China experts wrote to him,
warning that the deployment of the NMD would make U.S.-China
relations difficult.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, 35 U.S. scientists and engineers went to the
Capitol Hill to persuade Congress into rejecting the plan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, former high-ranking U.S. government officials,
including former secretary of state Henry Kissinger, former
presidential security advisors Zbigniew Brezezinki and Robert
McFarlane, as well as former defense secretaries William Perry and
Harold Brown, have asked Clinton to put off the decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Concludes Central Asia Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ASHKHABAD, Turkmenistan, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President
Jiang Zemin concluded his state visit to Turkmenistan and left
here Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan President Saparmurad Niyazov hosted a ceremony to
see Jiang and his party off at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Boarding the plane with Jiang back to China included Chinese
Vice Premier Qian Qichen, Minister in charge of State Development
Planning Commission Zeng Peiyan, Minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Shi Guangsheng and other senior officials.
</P>
<P>
During the past five days, Jiang paid a state visit to
Tajikistan and attended the fifth "Shanghai Five" summit.
</P>
<P>
The "Shanghai Five" nations are China, Tajikistan, Russia,
Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
