<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal, India Agree to Curb Border Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The India-Nepal Home Secretarial
Level Talks ended here Thursday night with an agreement to enhance
coordination between the two countries to counter cross-border
crimes, the Nepali Home Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Indian Home Secretary Kamal Pandey arrived here Tuesday for the
talks that began on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Our talks were chiefly focused on combating terrorism," said
Nepali Home Secretary Padam Pokharel. "As terrorism is a common
problem for both the countries, we have agreed to enhance
cooperation between the concerned officials on both sides to
counter it."
</P>
<P>
"The meeting has discussed the steps the two countries should
take to bring under control criminal activities across the border,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
Pokharel said both Nepal and India have agreed to set up a
joint local coordination committee for the purpose, comprising of
concerned Chief District Officers from Nepal and the District
Magistrates from the Indian side.
</P>
<P>
Nepal and India have 1700 km long open border which encourages
cross-border crimes and irregularities, such as smuggling,
abduction, unauthorized arms intrusions as well as trafficking of
women and children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
