<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Water, Sanitation Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
launched a major project funded by the Asian Development Bank to
provide drinking water and sanitary facilities to over one million
residents in the country, the official Daily News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lal Premnath, senior official with the National Water Service
and Drainage Board, Thursday told the newspaper that this project
which costs eight billion Rupees (105.3 million U.S. dollars), was
set off last January and is expected to be completed under three
phases by year 2006.
</P>
<P>
The work under the first stage will be completed in 26
Pradesiya Sabha ( Rural Council) areas in six districts within the
next six months, Premnath said.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to the Anuradhapura district in the
North Central Province and residents living in both urban and
rural areas in the district will receive drinking water under a
cluster project which will cost 3.2 billion Rupees (42.1 million U.
S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The balance of 4.8 billion Rupees (63.2 million U.S.dollars)
has been allocated equally to the other five districts of Puttalam,
Monaragala, Kalutara, Hambantota and Kegalle in separate provinces
of the country, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
