<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Set to Boost Oil Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's state oil company
Pertamina said it planned to boost oil production through the
development of marginal fields and by encouraging exploration in
deep water.
</P>
<P>
"There are many marginal fields that can boost oil production.
However, the government has to give incentives for the development
of those fields," the Indonesian Observer daily Friday quoted
Pertamina Exploration Director Gatot Wiroyudo as saying.
</P>
<P>
Wiroyudo said marginal fields had previously not been
considered commercially viable because of inefficiencies and poor
technology.
</P>
<P>
"We find that there are areas for efficiencies in exploration,
for example, there are cheaper oil platforms for offshore
activities. We also find that one well can be drilled for only 1.5
million U.S. dollars, compared with 5 million U.S. dollars before,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
"With those efficiencies and technology, marginal fields with
reserves of 10 million barrels of oil can be produced with an
average of around 8,000 bpd (barrels per day). That can be
commercial and we believe can help Indonesia boost oil production
in the future," he added.
</P>
<P>
Wiroyudo said there were about 40 potential marginal fields in
Indonesia, Asia's only member of OPEC. From those marginal fields
he predicted around 320,000 bpd could be pumped.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia produced 1.3 million bpd of crude oil and 150,000 bpd
of condensate in June, below its OPEC quota of 1.317 million bpd,
oil industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
However, Wiroyudo gave no timeframe for when the marginal
fields could begin production at the level of 320,000 bpd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
