<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Yields Over 177,000 Tons of Cotton in 1999-2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar produced 177,375 tons of
cotton in the fiscal year 1999-2000 which ended in March against
the target of 198,000 tons, official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The tonnage was produced out of a cultivated area of 341,820
hectares but the production target was not reached as it rained
abnormally in November last year, the non-rainy season, Myanmar
Minister of Agriculture and Irrigation Major-General Nyunt Tin was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government has purchased 24,750 tons of cotton in the year,
Nyunt Tin told a meeting here Thursday on extending cultivation of
industrial crops.
</P>
<P>
As there was adequate rain in June this year, the beginning of
the rainy season, the prospects of cotton cultivation look bright,
he added.
</P>
<P>
He called for placing emphasis on cultivation of cotton in
Mandalay, Sagaing and Magway divisions, the three central arid
zones in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar produced 4,765 tons
of cotton yarn and 17,823,000 meters of cotton fabrics in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, to maintain the enthusiasm of cotton growers and
relieve the shortage in investment capital, the government not
only provides more than one billion kyats (3 million U.S. dollars)
of loans to the cotton growers in the country annually, but also
grants advance payment for the purchase of cotton.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's locally-produced cotton fabrics are reportedly not
enough to meet the demand. It has to import from China, India,
Thailand and South Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0250 </DOCNO>
