<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safety of Foreigners Is Guaranteed in Laos: Deputy FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 7 (Xinhua) -- The Lao government has said that
the safety of foreigners is guaranteed in the country despite
several incidents happened recently, according to reports reaching
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The government has ordered the police in Vientiane and other
places of the country strengthen security measures to protect
foreign embassies and international organizations," Lao Deputy
Foreign Minister Pongsavath Boupa was quoted by a diplomatic
source in Vientiane, the Lao capital, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the foreign diplomats and representatives of
international organizations at a special meeting held in Vientiane
Thursday, Pongsavath denounced the rumors about big explosions and
large number of casualties occurred in the capital city as "
groundless".
</P>
<P>
"During the last few months, there are certain incidents of
explosions happened in Vientiane, leaving several injuries and
deaths, but they are all not very serious," he stated.
</P>
<P>
Describing those explosions as terrorist acts masterminded by
some anti-government activists to harm the stability and image of
the country, he said those incidents can not prevent foreigners to
see sights or do business in the country.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the e-mails of threats sent to the foreign
embassies and international organization delegates recently, the
official said those e-mails are "swashbuckling" and told foreign
delegates not to take them too seriously.
</P>
<P>
He promised that those kinds of threats will not happened any
more.
</P>
<P>
When asked about how the Lao government to deal with those
rebels who flu into Thailand and detained by Thai authority after
a clash at a Lao-Thai border check point, Pongsavath said the
government is now negotiating with Thai government and asking for
the extradition of those people.
</P>
<P>
The Lao detainees were among over 100 Lao rebels who on Monday
seized a Lao customs checkpoint across Sirindhorn district of Thai
border province of Ubon Rachathani, 629 kilometers northeast of
Bangkok, and clashed with Lao government troops, leading to
reportedly five dead and several injured.
</P>
<P>
The rebels was finally defeated by Lao government troops and
dispersed.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai had reaffirmed that the
government will not allow any armed groups to use the country for
activities against the Lao government.
</P>
<P>
The extradition of those people are now in negotiation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
