<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Riot Spreads to Waai in Maluku, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Renewed communal clashes spread on
Thursday to Waai village in Ambon, capital of Indonesia's Maluku
province, prompting hundreds of residents to flee to nearby
forests.
</P>
<P>
The Antara News Agency reported on Friday that the large scale
attacks were launched by Liang and Tulehu villagers arms with hand
guns, mortars, hand grenades, rifles and petroleum bombs.
</P>
<P>
The Waai villagers appeared to be virtually helpless in facing
the attackers, and many children and women abandoned their
villages and fled to nearby forests. Others had to walk great
distances to reach the villages of Passo and Wayari for help and
refuge.
</P>
<P>
The assailants were reported to have set fire on hundreds of
houses, school buildings and some houses of prayer in Waai village
which is only 28 kilometers from Ambon.
</P>
<P>
No details on casualties and material loss were immediately
available.
</P>
<P>
The death toll rose to 71 since communal violence returned in
Ambon on June 21. Hundreds have been injured during the period.
</P>
<P>
In Central Sulawesi, Wirabuana Military Commander Maj. Gen.
Slamet Kirbiantoro overseeing Sulawesi said that a total of 211
people had been confirmed dead as a result of the recent clashes
in Poso town.
</P>
<P>
He added the death toll in the violence was expected to rise as
the peacekeeping task force set up by the military command was
continuing to search for more bodies.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of communal violence in Poso broke out on May
23 and ended on June 4. It followed unrest on April 17 that
claimed two lives.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Post quoted observers as saying that the Poso
communal clashes are connected with the prolonged violence in
Maluku and North Maluku, where more than 3,000 people have been
killed since the conflict erupted in January last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
