<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Sweeps Through Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A heat wave is sweeping through
the Balkans which has resulted in the deaths of dozens of people.
</P>
<P>
Weather authorities said that the heat wave, which is caused by
a massive hot airflow from the Sahara desert, pushed temperatures
in the region to record highs this week.
</P>
<P>
In Greece, the temperature soared to 42 degrees Celsius on
Wednesday, leaving two people dead.
</P>
<P>
In Bulgaria, temperatures in most areas reached 40 degrees
Celsius, and the capital of Sofia recorded 39.9 degrees Celsius,
the hottest temperature in 112 years, leaving four people dead.
Temperatures rose to 42 degrees in Bucharest, killing six people.
</P>
<P>
The heat wave also sparked forest fires in Romania and Bulgaria.
It also affected Albania, Croatia, Yugoslavia, Bosnia and Moldova.
</P>
<P>
The heat wave is expected to continue in the next few days.
</P>
</TEXT>
