<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji's Military seeks Help from Tribal Chiefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Fiji's military would seek the
help of provincial tribal chiefs to negotiate the release of
ethnic Indian former prime minister Mahendra Chaudhry.
</P>
<P>
According to the Australian Associated Press, a delegation led
by the high chiefs from Naitasiri province met Fiji's military
leader, Commodore Frank Bainimarama, late Thursday last night at a
barracks near the capital Suva.
</P>
<P>
A local radio in Fiji reported Thursday the military had
accepted a whale's tooth, a traditional peace offering, from the
chiefs. Military spokesman Lieutenant-Colonel Filipo Tarakinikini
told the radio that Naitasiri leaders would mediate in talks later
in the day between Speight and Bainimarama.
</P>
<P>
The toppled ethnic Indian prime minister Chaudhry and other 26
officials have been held hostage for six weeks by an armed band
headed by George Speight.
</P>
<P>
The military has until now resisted allowing any direct
intervention by members of the influential Great Council of Chiefs
in negotiations with Speight. The number of the original hostages
was more than 40.
</P>
<P>
Social unrest have escalated around the country in the last
week. Landowners from Naitasiri province are demanding protection
of indigenous rights and around 300 of them staged a demonstration
in the capital city of Suva, rejecting an interim indigenous
civilian government sworn in by the military on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Suva and surrounding areas were plunged into darkness late
Thursday night and the international telephone service was
disrupted after the main hydro-electric plant was allegedly
sabotaged by landowners in the rural province of Monasavu. Much of
the country was getting its electricity from diesel generators
Friday.
</P>
<P>
On Fiji's second largest island, Vanua Levu, about 100
landowners have occupied the Labasa military camp, and the nearby
airport was closed by protesters for two hours Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
