<HEADLINE> Pak President Urges World to Persuade India for Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Describing Kashmir as a "nuclear
flash point", Pakistani President Rafiq Tarar Thursday called on
the international community to persuade India to enter into
meaningful dialogue with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"The world has now come to realize that durable peace between
Pakistan and India cannot be achieved without addressing the core
issue of Kashmir on priority basis," he stated while addressing a
function at the National Defense College of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"Kashmir is a test case of the viability and credibility of the
present international order," he added.
</P>
<P>
The president regretted that the attitude of the Indian
government has not been conducive to peace. "Their leaders
continue to make bellicose and provocative statements to build up
war hysteria," he said.
</P>
<P>
As a tangible sign of its belligerent posture, he said, New
Delhi announced a 28 percent increase in its defense budget and
this "additional allocation is larger than the entire defense
budget of Pakistan".
</P>
<P>
Tarar regretted that the subcontinent has seen "heightening of
tensions between Pakistan and India" for the past decade due to "
the struggle of the people of Kashmir for their right of self-
determination, as promised by the world community through U.N.
resolutions" .
</P>
<P>
Pakistan is committed to render moral, political and diplomatic
support to the cause of Kashmiris, he reiterated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
