<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, July 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The National Religious Party (NRP), a partner of
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's government, decided on
Thursday to quit the ruling coalition ahead of the tripartite
summit of Palestinians, Israel, and the United States slated for
July 11 near Washington.
</P>
<P>
The party's cabinet ministers and key members met at the office
of Housing and Construction Minister Yitzhak Levy and finally
decided to leave the government, the party said in an announcement.
(Israel-NRP-Resignation)- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- France Thursday again warned the United States of the
dangerous consequences from developing its National Missile
Defense (NMD) system, whose tests are due to resume Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the United States does not make the decision
without measuring the consequences for their European allies and
the reactions of China and Russia," said French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine. (France-US-NMD)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said on Thursday
that Britain's eventual membership of the euro, the European
single currency, was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
As one of Prime Minister Tony Blair most pro-euro ministers,
Cook said Britons could be won over to support it. But he also
made it clear that he was not calling for Britain to join the
single currency immediately. (UK-Cook-Euro)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BOGOTA -- Different government army offensives against rebels
and paramilitary Thursday in Colombia have left at least 29 dead
and an unknown number of wounded, said authorities.
</P>
<P>
At El Salero zone, close to La Sierra municipality, Cauca
department, western Colombia, a military faction killed 10 rebels
of Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC) and one from
National Liberation Army (ELN). (Colombia-Fighting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. National Transportation Safety Board (
NTSB) has concluded that John F. Kennedy Jr. lost control of the
single-engine plane he was flying last year, leading to the crash
that killed him, his wife and her sister.
</P>
<P>
In a final report issued Thursday on last year's July 19 crash
of the aircraft near Martha's Vineyard in Massachusetts State, the
United States, the NTSB said Kennedy, son of the late U.S.
president, had become disorientated during a descent over water at
night. (US-Pilot-Error-Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- The German parliament Thursday approved a 10 billion-
mark bill to compensate former forced and slave laborers in Nazi
era.
</P>
<P>
The bill, based on a draft agreement between Berlin and
Washington earlier this year, commits the German government and
business to collect 5 billion marks each (2.45 billion U.S.
dollars) for a compensation fund for holocaust victims during
World War II. (Germany-Compensation Bill)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. and Vietnamese trade negotiators Thursday
kicked off two days of talks aiming to finalize a historic market-
opening pact.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky
and Vietnamese Trade Minister Vu Khoan are expected to hammer out
details of the proposed bilateral trade agreement, a result of
four years of on-and-off negotiations. (US-Vietnam-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The European Court of First Instance ruled Thursday
that German car maker Volkswagen should be fined with 90 million
euros (86 million U.S. dollars) for its violation of European
Union's (EU's) competition law.
</P>
<P>
The court in a judgment upholds a decision of the European
Commission, the EU's executive body, against Volkswagen
establishing very serious infringement of EU Competition Rules,
the EU Commission said. (EU-Volkswagen)
</P>
