<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Cup Vote Hit by 'Bribe' Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- FIFA's decision to award Germany the
2006 World Cup has been hit by revelations that delegates received
letters offering cash gifts in exchange for votes.
</P>
<P>
Jack Warner, the Trinidad representative on FIFA's executive
committee, confirmed to BBC News 24 that he and several of his
colleagues woke up on Thursday morning to
find letters pushed under the doors of their hotel rooms in Zurich.
</P>
<P>
He revealed the letters claimed to be from someone supporting
the German campaign and offered a cash gift in return for their
support in the crucial vote.
</P>
<P>
Warner said he and the other delegates believed the letter to
be a hoax, but added that the matter was discussed ahead of the
final ballot and that FIFA president Sepp Blatter was upset and
very angry at the news.
</P>
<P>
The revelations will cast doubt on the process which saw
Germany pip South Africa by one vote for the right to host the
prestigious tournament, and are likely to prompt an investigation.
</P>
<P>
Attention may also focus on the New Zealand delegate Charles
Dempsey, whose abstention from the final round of voting handed
the Germans victory.
</P>
<P>
It has also been revealed that South Africa's campaign leader
Danny Jordaan had been told to return to Zurich in the light of
the revelations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
