<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French League Elects New Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- France's national soccer league (LNF)
voted a new chairman on Thursday in a close contest fought out
over the fate of income from lucrative television rights.
</P>
<P>
Gerard Bourgoin, former vice-president of first division AJ
Auxerre, edged Noel Le Graet by 45 votes to 43 in an election by
the LNF's 92-member board. Two ballots were blank and two were
spoiled.
</P>
<P>
Le Graet, who had been seeking a third four-year term, favors
an equitable share-out among clubs of the revenue from the sale of
rights to televise French soccer.
</P>
<P>
Bourgoin wants more money to go to bigger clubs on the grounds
that the income would help elite sides keep their best players in
France.
</P>
<P>
He had the support of the presidents of top clubs Lyon, Lens
and champions Monaco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
