<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Foreign Minister to Visit Japan, China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy announced his upcoming visits to Japan and China here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day stay between July 12 and 13 in Miyazaki,
Japan,Axworthy will meet with his counterparts from the G-8
countries on"conflict prevention, arms control and disarmament,
terrorism,organized crime as well as the environment," the
minister said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The G-8 foreign minister meeting will also be devoted to issues
"including the Balkans, Africa, the Middle East Peace Process and
South Asia," according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Axworthy visits China between July 14 and 15, during which he
will discuss a wide range of topics, including matters related
with the United Nation Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"Canada and China cooperate on a wide spectrum of global and
regional foreign policy issues both bilaterally and within the
framework of the United Nations and the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations," said the minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Set up Task Force for Global IT Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The three-day U.N. Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC) meeting
has discussed development and international cooperation in the
21st century and the role of IT in the context of a knowledge-
based global economy.
</P>
<P>
Conference participants noted that the emerging new economy
still remains concentrated in the developed countries, and unless
access to IT is broadened, the majority of people particularly in
the developing nations will not enjoy the benefits of the
knowledge-based economy.
</P>
<P>
To bridge the "digital divide", the international community
should address the major impediments to the participation of the
majority of the people in the IT revolution such as lack of
infrastructure, education, capacity building, investment and
connectivity, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
U.N. figures show that the fifth of the world's people living
in the highest income countries have 86% of world's GDP and 93% of
internet users, while the bottom fifth have only 1% of GDP and 0.2%
of internet users.
</P>
<P>
Delegates emphasized the importance of broader involvement of
governments, multilateral agencies and bilateral donors in the
process as market forces alone cannot cope with the task.
</P>
<P>
Efforts for transfer of technology to developing countries on
concessional and preferential terms are encouraged.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. and its agencies are asked to play a key role in
promoting synergy and coherence of all efforts to expand the
development impact of IT.
</P>
<P>
ECOSOC's working group is expected to make recommendations to
the U.N. Millennium Assembly in September and the mid-July summit
of the Group of 8 countries to be held in Okinawa, Japan and to
focus on IT issues, according to ECOSOC President, Indonesia's
Makarim Wibisono. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Calls for Saving Hard Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Cuban authorities Friday called
again on people to reduce the spending of hard currency because of
the high prices of oil in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Finances and Prices Minister Manuel Millares made this call
when he toured the western province of Matanzas, some 100
kilometers east of Havana.
</P>
<P>
Although the extraction of crude grows gradually in the island,
it is not enough to supply the needs of the country, which depends
on the import of hydrocarbons and byproducts.
</P>
<P>
Cuban crude is used as fuel to generate 70 percent of the
electricity demand of the island.
</P>
<P>
Economy and Planning Minister Jose Luis Rodriguez explained in
a recent meeting with the presidents of the provincial governments
that the price of a Brent crude barrel goes from 28 to 30 U.S.
dollars, well above the 21 to 22 dollars foreseen by the island
finance authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
