<HEADLINE> Gore Focuses Presidential Campaign on Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
focused his presidential campaign on women Friday by pushing his
agenda for health care reform.
</P>
<P>
In a speech in Pennsylvania, Gore said that he would fight drug-
patent extensions that would be "bad medicine for the American
people," especially women.
</P>
<P>
Gore is wrapping up the fourth and final week of his"prosperity
and progress tour", which is aimed at claiming credit for the
nation's robust economy and also seeking to reshape the campaign
debate into a discussion of how to spend the projected budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
The presumptive Democratic presidential nominee criticized
Republicans in Congress for forming league with drug companies in
pushing patent protections for drugs that cost consumers billions.
</P>
<P>
He contended that women are the biggest victims of "price
gouging and profiteering" by the drug industry.
</P>
<P>
Gore said that women pay more for prescription drugs, live
longer and earn less than men, and have higher overall health
costs, making them the biggest winner under his proposal to
bolster Medicare.
</P>
<P>
"Women's health care often costs as much or more than men's,
even though women have fewer dollars to spend on it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"As president, I'll lead the fight to stop these unfair patent
extensions," said Gore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
