<DOCNO> XIE20000707.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise on More Signs of Slowing Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stock ended higher
Friday as a government report raised hope that the slowing U.S.
economy will prompt the Federal Reserve to end the year-long
cycle of interest rate hikes.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 154.51 at 10,635.98
and the technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 62.63 at 4,
023.20.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor'
s 500 index rose 22.23 at 1,478.90.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied after the U.S. Labor Department reported
that private employers added 206,000 in June but the addition of
jobs was offset by the departure of 190,000 temporary workers from
the census. Therefore, total payrolls in the month increased by
only 11,000.
</P>
<P>
The employment report convinced investors that the Federal
Reserve was succeeding in slowing the U.S. economy and the current
monetary tightening cycle is nearly over.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates six times in the
past year in an effort to prevent the economy from overheating and
keep inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
The lower-than-expected job increase drove the financial and
retail sectors higher. The financial companies including Chase
Manhattan and BankAmerica rose while retailers such as Home Depot
and Wal-Mart were also up.
</P>
<P>
On the tech sector, Texas Instruments and Gateway rose but
Qualcomm and Yahoo fell.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index rose 8.61 at 654.36 and the American Stock
Exchange index rose 8.60 at 936.48. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 4.90 at 528.22.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,813 up, 1,105 down and 448
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 929.19 million shares from 943.31
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
