<HEADLINE> Mexico Seizes 32 Archaeological Pieces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-two archaeological pieces
were seized in the northwestern Mexican state of Nayarit, and the
person who was transporting them was detained, the Federal
Attorney General Office (PGR) delegation in that state said Friday.
</P>
<P>
A PGR communique said that Federal Judicial Police (PJF)
agents detained the driver of a Datsun light truck in the Eastern
Detour Road, at the crossing that leads to the Xalisco
municipality.
</P>
<P>
The light truck driver, Luis Gonzalo Garcia, stepped down from
the cabin in a way that picked the curiosity of the agents, who
asked him to show what he was transporting, and discovered a
cardboard box containing 32 prehispanic pieces.
</P>
<P>
The seized pieces are 16 earthenware pots, two plates of the
same material, ten bowls, a volcanic stone mortar with pestle, the
fragment of a head, another of a leg and the lid of a pot.
</P>
<P>
The pieces were classified by archaeologists into four cultural
horizons of Nayarit, in the northwest of Mexico, which go from the
Tumbas de Tiro Tradition, passing through Aztlan, Mololoa, and
Santa Cruz, 300 years BC to 1300 AD.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
